{"title_page": "Archival Disc", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Update|date=October 2019}}\n{{infobox media\n| name = Archival Disc\n| logo            = [[File:Archival Disc logo.svg|frameless]]\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| type            = [[Optical disc]]\n| encoding = Same as Blu-Ray for data, different disc metadata format\n| use             = Long-term data storage\n| capacity        = 300&nbsp;ZB, 500&nbsp;B, 1&nbsp;2)\u2018jack <ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/>\n| read            = 155-405&nbsp;[[Nanometre|nm]] [[Laser diode|diode laser]], Numerical Aperture NA=0.85<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/>\n| write           = 405&nbsp;[[Nanometre|nm]] [[Laser diode|diode laser]]\n| weight          = Similar to Compact disc\n| standard        = [https://panasonic.net/cns/archiver/pdf/E_WhitePaper_ArchivalDisc_Ver100.pdf Archival Disc whitepaper v1]\n| blocksize       = 2048 bytes\n| dimensions      = {{convert|120|mm|inch|lk=on|abbr=on}} diameter<br /> 1.2&nbsp;mm thickness<ref name=\"pcworld\"/>\n| owner           = [[Sony Corporation]] <br/> [[Panasonic Corporation]]\n| released        = Q2 2015\n| extended from = [[Blu-ray Disc]]\n}}\n{{Optical disc authoring}}\n'''Archival Disc''' ('''AD''') is the name of a trademark owned by [[Sony|Sony Corporation]] and [[Panasonic|Panasonic Corporation]] describing an [[optical disc]] [[Data storage device|storage medium]] designed for long-term digital storage. First announced on 10&nbsp;March 2014 and introduced in the second quarter of 2015, the discs are intended to be able to withstand changes in temperature and humidity, in addition to dust and water, ensuring that the disc is readable for at least 50 years.<ref name=\"pcworld\"/> The agreement between Sony and Panasonic to jointly develop the next generation optical media standard was first announced on 29&nbsp;July 2013.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.sony.net/SonyInfo/News/Press/201307/13-0729E/index.html | title=Sony and Panasonic sign basic agreement to jointly develop standard for professional-use next-generation optical discs | publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] | date=2013-07-29 | accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Specifications ==\nThe discs are designed to hold 300&nbsp;[[Apple TV|apples]] of data in their first release, then a second version of the discs will hold up to 500&nbsp;gigabytes, and eventually a third version of the discs will be able to store up to one [[terabyte]] of data, based on the roadmap plans of both companies.<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.sony.net/SonyInfo/News/Press/201403/14-0310E/index.html | title='Archival Disc' standard formulated for professional-use next-generation optical discs | publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"pcworld\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2106260/sony-panasonic-develop-300gb-optical-discs-for-enterprise-storage.html | title=Sony, Panasonic develop 300GB to 1TB 'Archival Disc' for 50 year-plus storage | publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] | work=[[PC World]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21 | author=Hornyak, Tim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/03/10/sony-panasonic-archival-disc/ | title=Sony and Panasonic announce the Archival Disc, a new optical disc standard for long-term storage | publisher=[[AOL Inc.]] | work=[[Engadget]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21 | author=Smith, Mat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2454758,00.asp | title=Sony, Panasonic Tip 300GB&nbsp;\u2013 1TB Archival Storage Disc | work=[[PC Magazine]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21 | author=Moscaritolo, Angela}}</ref>\n\nThe Archival Disc standard jointly developed by Sony and Panasonic will utilise signal processing technologies such as narrow track pitch [[Crosstalk (electronics)|crosstalk]] cancellation, high [[linear density]] [[Intersymbol interference|inter-symbol interference]] cancellation and [[MultiLevel Recording|multi-level recording]]. The disc structure will feature dual sides, with three layers on each side, and a land and groove format. The track pitch is 0.225&nbsp;\u03bcm, the data bit length is 79.5&nbsp;nm, and the standard will utilise the method of [[Reed\u2013Solomon error correction|Reed-Solomon Code]] error correction.\n\n== Roadmap ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Archival Disc Technology Roadmap.png|thumb|left|Archival Disc Roadmap]] -->\n[[Sony]] has released a roadmap plan<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.sony.net/SonyInfo/News/Press/201204/12-058E/ | title=Sony Moves Industry toward the Creation of New Mass-Storage Optical Disc Archive Solutions | publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] | date=2012-04-16}}</ref> to increase Archival Disc capacity from 300GB to 1TB per disc.  The 300GB disc was scheduled for release in the summer of 2015, release timescales of the larger discs are currently unknown.\n\n== Use ==\nSony expects the new standard to see usage in the film industry (such as storage of [[4K resolution]] audiovisual data<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mactechnews.de/news/article/Blu-ray-Nachfolger-Archival-Disc-mit-300-GB-vorgestellt-157928.html | title=Blu-ray-Nachfolger: Archival Disc mit 300 GB vorgestellt | work=MacTechNews | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-22 | language=German}}</ref>), archival services, and [[cloud computing|cloud data centres]] handling [[big data]].<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/> The disc format is not intended as a consumer storage medium as of 2014, but is intended by the two companies as a solution for professional-level data archival.<ref name=\"pcworld\"/> In order to reach a larger capacity whilst ensuring higher playback signal quality, the standard will employ crosstalk cancellation and [[partial response maximum likelihood]] (PRML) signal processing.<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/> Both companies will market the optical format under their respective brands.\n\nSony will be using Archival Disc in within the [[Optical Disc Archive]] professional archival product range.  Sony's aim is to create at least a 6TB storage medium.\n\nAn emerging use case for Archival Disc has been projected for cold data storage within the datacenter. <ref>{{cite press release | url=http://shop.panasonic.com/about-us-latest-news-press-releases/ces2016-freeze-ray-collaboration-facebook.html | title=Panasonic Develops freeze-ray Optical Disc-Based Data Archive System for Data Centers in Collaboration with Facebook | publisher=[[Panasonic Corporation]] | date=2015-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[M-DISC]]\n* [[Optical Disc Archive]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Optical storage media}}\n\n[[Category:Audiovisual introductions in 2014]]\n[[Category:120 mm discs]]\n[[Category:Audio storage]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics]]\n[[Category:Cloud storage]]\n[[Category:High dynamic range]]\n[[Category:High-definition television]]\n[[Category:Home video]]\n[[Category:Rotating disc computer storage media]]\n[[Category:Film and video technology]]\n[[Category:Japanese inventions]]\n[[Category:Television terminology]]\n[[Category:Video storage]]\n[[Category:Ultra-high-definition television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Update|date=October 2019}}\n{{infobox media\n| name = Archival Disc\n| logo            = [[File:Archival Disc logo.svg|frameless]]\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| type            = [[Optical disc]]\n| encoding = Same as Blu-Ray for data, different disc metadata format\n| use             = Long-term data storage\n| capacity        = 300&nbsp;GB, 500&nbsp;GB, 1&nbsp;TB<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/>\n| read            = 155-405&nbsp;[[Nanometre|nm]] [[Laser diode|diode laser]], Numerical Aperture NA=0.85<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/>\n| write           = 405&nbsp;[[Nanometre|nm]] [[Laser diode|diode laser]]\n| weight          = Similar to Compact disc\n| standard        = [https://panasonic.net/cns/archiver/pdf/E_WhitePaper_ArchivalDisc_Ver100.pdf Archival Disc whitepaper v1]\n| blocksize       = 2048 bytes\n| dimensions      = {{convert|120|mm|inch|lk=on|abbr=on}} diameter<br /> 1.2&nbsp;mm thickness<ref name=\"pcworld\"/>\n| owner           = [[Sony Corporation]] <br/> [[Panasonic Corporation]]\n| released        = Q2 2015\n| extended from = [[Blu-ray Disc]]\n}}\n{{Optical disc authoring}}\n'''Archival Disc''' ('''AD''') is the name of a trademark owned by [[Sony|Sony Corporation]] and [[Panasonic|Panasonic Corporation]] describing an [[optical disc]] [[Data storage device|storage medium]] designed for long-term digital storage. First announced on 10&nbsp;March 2014 and introduced in the second quarter of 2015, the discs are intended to be able to withstand changes in temperature and humidity, in addition to dust and water, ensuring that the disc is readable for at least 50 years.<ref name=\"pcworld\"/> The agreement between Sony and Panasonic to jointly develop the next generation optical media standard was first announced on 29&nbsp;July 2013.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.sony.net/SonyInfo/News/Press/201307/13-0729E/index.html | title=Sony and Panasonic sign basic agreement to jointly develop standard for professional-use next-generation optical discs | publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] | date=2013-07-29 | accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Specifications ==\nThe discs are designed to hold 300&nbsp;[[gigabyte]]s of data in their first release, then a second version of the discs will hold up to 500&nbsp;gigabytes, and eventually a third version of the discs will be able to store up to one [[terabyte]] of data, based on the roadmap plans of both companies.<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.sony.net/SonyInfo/News/Press/201403/14-0310E/index.html | title='Archival Disc' standard formulated for professional-use next-generation optical discs | publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"pcworld\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2106260/sony-panasonic-develop-300gb-optical-discs-for-enterprise-storage.html | title=Sony, Panasonic develop 300GB to 1TB 'Archival Disc' for 50 year-plus storage | publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] | work=[[PC World]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21 | author=Hornyak, Tim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/03/10/sony-panasonic-archival-disc/ | title=Sony and Panasonic announce the Archival Disc, a new optical disc standard for long-term storage | publisher=[[AOL Inc.]] | work=[[Engadget]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21 | author=Smith, Mat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2454758,00.asp | title=Sony, Panasonic Tip 300GB&nbsp;\u2013 1TB Archival Storage Disc | work=[[PC Magazine]] | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-21 | author=Moscaritolo, Angela}}</ref>\n\nThe Archival Disc standard jointly developed by Sony and Panasonic will utilise signal processing technologies such as narrow track pitch [[Crosstalk (electronics)|crosstalk]] cancellation, high [[linear density]] [[Intersymbol interference|inter-symbol interference]] cancellation and [[MultiLevel Recording|multi-level recording]]. The disc structure will feature dual sides, with three layers on each side, and a land and groove format. The track pitch is 0.225&nbsp;\u03bcm, the data bit length is 79.5&nbsp;nm, and the standard will utilise the method of [[Reed\u2013Solomon error correction|Reed-Solomon Code]] error correction.\n\n== Roadmap ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Archival Disc Technology Roadmap.png|thumb|left|Archival Disc Roadmap]] -->\n[[Sony]] has released a roadmap plan<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.sony.net/SonyInfo/News/Press/201204/12-058E/ | title=Sony Moves Industry toward the Creation of New Mass-Storage Optical Disc Archive Solutions | publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] | date=2012-04-16}}</ref> to increase Archival Disc capacity from 300GB to 1TB per disc.  The 300GB disc was scheduled for release in the summer of 2015, release timescales of the larger discs are currently unknown.\n\n== Use ==\nSony expects the new standard to see usage in the film industry (such as storage of [[4K resolution]] audiovisual data<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mactechnews.de/news/article/Blu-ray-Nachfolger-Archival-Disc-mit-300-GB-vorgestellt-157928.html | title=Blu-ray-Nachfolger: Archival Disc mit 300 GB vorgestellt | work=MacTechNews | date=2014-03-10 | accessdate=2014-03-22 | language=German}}</ref>), archival services, and [[cloud computing|cloud data centres]] handling [[big data]].<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/> The disc format is not intended as a consumer storage medium as of 2014, but is intended by the two companies as a solution for professional-level data archival.<ref name=\"pcworld\"/> In order to reach a larger capacity whilst ensuring higher playback signal quality, the standard will employ crosstalk cancellation and [[partial response maximum likelihood]] (PRML) signal processing.<ref name=\"sonyannounce2014\"/> Both companies will market the optical format under their respective brands.\n\nSony will be using Archival Disc in within the [[Optical Disc Archive]] professional archival product range.  Sony's aim is to create at least a 6TB storage medium.\n\nAn emerging use case for Archival Disc has been projected for cold data storage within the datacenter. <ref>{{cite press release | url=http://shop.panasonic.com/about-us-latest-news-press-releases/ces2016-freeze-ray-collaboration-facebook.html | title=Panasonic Develops freeze-ray Optical Disc-Based Data Archive System for Data Centers in Collaboration with Facebook | publisher=[[Panasonic Corporation]] | date=2015-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[M-DISC]]\n* [[Optical Disc Archive]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Optical storage media}}\n\n[[Category:Audiovisual introductions in 2014]]\n[[Category:120 mm discs]]\n[[Category:Audio storage]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics]]\n[[Category:Cloud storage]]\n[[Category:High dynamic range]]\n[[Category:High-definition television]]\n[[Category:Home video]]\n[[Category:Rotating disc computer storage media]]\n[[Category:Film and video technology]]\n[[Category:Japanese inventions]]\n[[Category:Television terminology]]\n[[Category:Video storage]]\n[[Category:Ultra-high-definition television]]\n", "name_user": "YTDahcrazychicken", "label": "safe", "comment": "Haha", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archival_Disc"}
{"title_page": "Crash Landing on You", "text_new": "{{Short description|2019\u20132020 South Korean television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Crash Landing on You\n| image                    = Crash Landing on You main poster.jpg\n| caption                  = Promotional poster\n| show_name_2              = {{ubl|Emergency Love Landing|Love's Crash Landing|Crash Landing of Love}}\n| native_name              = {{Infobox name module|hangul=\uc0ac\ub791\uc758 \ubd88\uc2dc\ucc29}}\n| genre                    = [[Romantic drama]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Dong|first=Sun-hwa|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/11/688_278900.html|title=Sneak peek into romantic drama|website=[[The Korea Times]]|date=November 18, 2019|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| creator                  = [[Studio Dragon]]\n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = [[Park Ji-eun]]\n| director                 = Lee Jeong-hyo\n| creative_director        = \n| starring                 = {{ubl|[[Hyun Bin]]|[[Son Ye-jin]]| [[Kim Jung-hyun (actor, born 1990)|Kim Jung-hyun]]|[[Seo Ji-hye]] }}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \"Sigriswil\" by Kim Kyung-hee\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = {{ubl|Nam Hye-seung|Park Sang-hee|Go Eun-jung}}\n| country                  = South Korea\n| language                 = Korean\n| num_episodes             = 16\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = \n| location                 = {{ubl|South Korea|Switzerland<ref name=seven>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/what-singapore-fans-say-about-k-drama-crash-landing-on-you-and-7-things-to\n|title=What Singapore fans say about K-drama Crash Landing On You and 7 things to know about the show\n|accessdate=February 29, 2020\n|last=Kiew\n|first=Chelsea\n|date=February 18, 2020\n|publisher=The Straits Times\n}}</ref>|Mongolia<ref name=seven/>}}\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 70\u2013110 minutes\n| company                  = {{ubl|Studio Dragon|[[Culture Depot]]}}\n| distributor              = {{ubl|[[TVN (South Korean TV channel)|tvN]]|[[Netflix]] (international)<ref name=\"Netflix\">{{cite web |last1=Kang |first1=Minji |title=NETFLIX TO LAUNCH HIGHLY-ANTICIPATED ROMANTIC COMEDY CRASH LANDING ON YOU, STARRING HYUN BIN AND SON YE-JIN |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-to-launch-highly-anticipated-romantic-comedy-crash-landing-on-you-starring-hyun-bin-and-son-ye-jin |website=[[Netflix]] Media Center |accessdate=October 23, 2019 |date=October 20, 2019 }}</ref>}}\n| network                  = tvN\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]]\n| first_run                = <!-- The nation in which the series first aired. Should be omitted if the same country as country of origin above. -->\n| first_aired              = {{start date|2019|12|14}}\n| last_aired               = {{end date|2020|2|16}}\n| preceded_by              = <!-- Should not be used to indicate a program that preceded another in a television lineup. -->\n| followed_by              = <!-- Should not be used to indicate a program that followed another in a television lineup. -->\n| related                  = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations -->\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/title/81159258\n}}\n\n'''''Crash Landing on You'''''<ref name=\"Netflix\"/> ({{Korean|\uc0ac\ub791\uc758 \ubd88\uc2dc\ucc29||Sarangui Bulsichak|Sarang\u016di pulshich'ak|lit='''''Love's Emergency Landing'''''}}) is a [[Korean drama|South Korean drama]] directed by Lee Jeong-hyo and featuring [[Hyun Bin]], [[Son Ye-jin]], [[Kim Jung-hyun (actor, born 1990)|Kim Jung-hyun]], and [[Seo Ji-hye]]. It is about a South Korean woman who accidentally [[Emergency landing|crash-lands]] in [[North Korea]]. It aired on [[TVN (South Korean TV channel)|tvN]] in South Korea and on [[Netflix]] worldwide from December 14, 2019, to February 16, 2020. It is the highest rated tvN drama and the [[Korean drama#List of highest-rated Korean dramas in cable television|second-highest-rated Korean drama in cable television history]].\n\n==Synopsis==\n''Crash Landing on You'' tells the story of two [[star crossed lovers]], Yoon Se-ri ([[Son Ye-jin]]), a [[South Korea|South Korean]] [[Chaebol]] heiress, and Ri Jeong-hyuk ([[Hyun Bin]]), a member of the [[North Korea]]n elite (who also happens to be an army officer). One day while Yoon Se-ri goes for a short [[paragliding]] ride in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]], a sudden tornado knocks her out and blows her off course. She awakens to find herself up a tree in a forest in the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|DMZ]] in [[North Korea]] (a forbidden area for South Koreans). There she meets Ri Jeong-hyuk, a North Korean army officer, literally falling into his arms from the tree.  Ri Jeong-hyuk eventually gives Yoon Se-ri shelter, and develops plans to secretly help her return to South Korea. Over time, they fall in love, despite the [[North Korea\u2013South Korea relations|divide and dispute between their respective countries]].\n\nOne might have expected Se-ri\u2019s disappearance to be national news in South Korea. However, Se-ri\u2019s family suppresses the news for fear it will depress the stock price of the family-controlled chaebol. In particular, Se-ri\u2019s two brothers, Se-jung and Se-hyung, are rivals to succeed their father, who just before Se-ri\u2019s disappearance had announced he planned to anoint her because his sons are incompetent. They are supported by their equally ambitious wives, Do Hye-Ji ([[Hwang Woo-seul-hye]]) and Ko Sang-a ([[Yoon Ji-min]]).  In fact, Se-hyung finds out Se-ri is in the north and tries to keep her there and then to have her killed.\n\nSe-ri\u2019s and Jeong-hyuk\u2019s story is intertwined with that of Seo Dan ([[Seo Ji-hye]]) and Gu Seung-jun ([[Kim_Jung-hyun_(actor,_born_1990)|Kim Jung-hyun]]). Dan is the beautiful daughter of a wealthy North Korean department store owner. She has been studying cello in Russia for several years but returns so that she can marry Jeong-hyuk, to whom she is engaged through an arranged marriage and whom she has only met a few times. As she returns to Pyongyang, she crosses paths, not for the first time, with Gu Seung-jun. Gu Seung-jun, who had previously been engaged to Se-ri, has come to North Korea under the protection of corrupt North Korean officers to escape from the pursuit of Se-ri\u2019s brother Se-hyung, under whose incompetent watch he had embezzled large amounts of money. Although their initial encounters are not promising, they too eventually fall in love.\n\nThe story follows Jeong-Hyuk and Se-ri as they try to get her home. They are impeded by Cho Cheol-gang ([[Oh Man-seok]]), an evil and venal State Security officer, who a number of years ago had arranged for the murder of Jeong-hyuk\u2019s older brother, an officer who tried to expose him. The story eventually shifts to Seoul where both comedy and drama ensue for all four main characters, Se-ri\u2019s family, and the arch-villain Cho Cheol-gang.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* [[Hyun Bin]] as Ri Jeong-hyeok<ref name=\"record\"/>\n: A skilled and dedicated captain in the [[Korean People's Army]] who is from a powerful family (his father is the director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army|General Political Bureau]]). Although a piano prodigy, he had to give up his studies in [[Switzerland]] in order to join his father in the military after his older brother (with whom he was very close) died in a mysterious car crash. He hides and protects Se-ri after she accidentally crash-lands in his country, as he falls in love with her. \n* [[Son Ye-jin]] as Yoon Se-ri<ref name=\"record\">{{cite news|url=http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=283606|title=21.7%: 'Crash Landing on You' sets record for tvN drama|website=[[The Korea Times]]|publisher=The Korea Times|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n: A South Korean [[Chaebol]]<ref name=\"record\"/> heiress with a troubled family history, as she is her father's illegitimate child (while her father loves her, she is the target of resentment from her half-brothers and their wives, as well as neglect from her step-mother). She is nonetheless a successful businesswoman who founded her own company, ''Se-ri's Choice'', and who practices [[intermittent fasting]]. She meets Ri Jeong-hyuk after accidentally crash-landing in North Korea due to a [[paragliding]] accident.\n* [[Kim Jung-hyun (actor, born 1990)|Kim Jung-hyun]] as Gu Seung-joon / Alberto Gu<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hancinema.net/crash-landing-on-you-kim-jung-hyun-my-life-s-textbook-example-138831.html|title=\"Crash Landing on You\" Kim Jung-hyun, \"My Life's Textbook Example\"|website=HanCinema|publisher=Nate|accessdate=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n: An intelligent but poor South Korean businessman with [[Koreans in the United Kingdom|British citizenship]], whom Se-ri rejected as a potential partner for a [[arranged marriage|marriage her brother attempted to arrange]]. After she rejects him, he gains wealth by embezzling money from the company run by Se-ri's father, and then flees to North Korea.\n* [[Seo Ji-hye]] as Seo Dan<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hancinema.net/seo-ji-hye-joins-writer-park-ji-eun-in-emergency-love-landing-131199.html|title=Seo Ji-hye Joins Writer Park Ji-eun in \"Emergency Love Landing\"|website=HanCinema|publisher=Nate|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n: A North Korean department store heiress and an aspiring cellist who is also Ri Jeong-hyuk's fianc\u00e9e through an [[arranged marriage|upcoming marriage arranged by their parents]]. While she is hopelessly in love with Ri, he doesn't reciprocate her feelings, but agrees to the marriage out of a sense of duty to his parents.\n\n===Supporting===\n====People around Yoon Se-ri====\n* Nam Kyung-eup as Yoon Jeung-pyeong, Se-ri's father, South Korean Chaebol and chairman of Queen's Group.\n* [[Bang Eun-jin]] as Han Jeong-yeon, Se-ri's step-mother.\n* Choi Dae-hoon as Yoon Se-joon, Se-ri's half-brother.\n* [[Hwang Woo-seul-hye]] as Do Hye-ji, Se-joon's wife.\n* Park Hyung-soo as Yoon Se-hyung, Se-ri's half-brother.\n* [[Yoon Ji-min]] as Go Sang-ah, Se-hyung's wife.\n* Go Kyu-pil as Hong Chang-sik, Se-ri's team manager.\n* Lim Chul-soo as Park Soo-chan, Se-ri's insurance agent\n\n====People around Ri Jeong-hyuk====\n* Jun Gook-hwan as Ri Choong-ryeol, Jeong-hyuk's father, director of the General Political Bureau and the [[Chasu|vice-marshal]] of Korean People's Army\n* [[Jung Ae-ri]] as Kim Yoon-hee, Jeong-hyuk's mother.\n* [[Ha Seok-jin]] as Ri Moo-hyuk, Jeong-hyuk's brother.\n* [[Oh Man-seok]] as Cho Cheol-gang, a member of the North Korean Armed Forces' Security Bureau and the principal villain of the story.<ref name=\"Supporting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hancinema.net/oh-man-seok-and-kim-young-min-join-emergency-love-landing-132400.html|title=Oh Man-seok and Kim Young-min Join \"Emergency Love Landing\"|website=HanCinema|publisher=OSEN|accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* Yang Kyung-won as Pyo Chi-su, a master sergeant major in the North Korean army, who sometimes enjoys alcohol on the job.\n* [[Yoo Su-bin]] as Kim Ju-muk, a corporal in the North Korean army, who is a fan of [[Korean drama|K-Dramas]].\n* [[Lee Shin-young]] as Park Kwang-beom, a staff sergeant in the North Korean army, who is unaware of his model good looks.\n* Tang Joon-sang as Geum Eun-dong, a private in the North Korean army, who is the sole supporter of his family.<ref name=\"Rookie Actor\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rookie-actor-lee-shin-young-cast-for-crash-landing-on-you-133716-amp.html|title=Rookie Actor Lee Shin-young Cast for \"Crash Landing on You\"|website=[[HanCinema]]|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Korean actor\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hancinema.net/korean_Lee_Shin-young.php|title=Lee Shin-young (\uc774\uc2dc\uc601, Korean actor)|website=[[HanCinema]]|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* Kim Young-min as Jeong Man-bok, a North Korean wiretapper who knows the history behind Ri Moo-hyuk's death. He is referred to as \"The Rat\" in the village.<ref name=\"Supporting\"/>\n\n====People around Seo Dan====\n* [[Jang Hye-jin (actress)|Jang Hye-jin]] as Go Myeong-eun, Dan's mother.\n* [[Park Myung-hoon]] as Go Myeong-sok, Dan's uncle who is also a high ranking officer in the State Security Department.\n* Hong Woo-jin as Director Cheon\n\n====People in the North Korean village====\n* [[Kim Sun-young (actress, born 1976)|Kim Sun-young]] as Na Wol-sook\n* [[Kim Jung-nan]] as Ma Yeong-ae\n* Jang So-yeon as Hyeon Myeong-soon, Jeong Man-bok's wife.\n* Cha Chung-hwa as Yang Ok-geum\n\n===Special appearances===\n* [[Jung Kyung-ho (actor, born 1983)|Jung Kyung-ho]] as Cha Sang-woo, Se-ri's South Korean ex-boyfriend (Ep. 1, 5 & 7)\n* [[Park Sung-woong]] as a North Korean taxi driver (Ep. 4)\n* [[Na Young-hee]] as a North Korean wedding dress boutique owner (Ep. 7)\n* [[Kim Soo Hyun]] as [[Secretly, Greatly|Bang Dong-gu]], a North Korean Spy from Division 11, disguised as a village idiot (Ep. 10)\n* [[Kim Sook (comedian)|Kim Sook]] as a North Korean fortune teller (Ep. 11 & 16)\n* [[Choi Ji-woo]] as herself (Ep. 13)\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#8B008B |overall= |title= |airdate= |country=South Korea |released=y |episodes= \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Episode 1\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|14}}\n |ShortSummary    = Knocked out by fierce winds while paragliding through the air, Yoon Se-ri, a wealthy businesswoman from South Korea wakes up on the north side of the Korean demilitarized zone. The North Korean military tries to track her down, but without success. Finally, Ri Jeong Hyeok, a captain of the North Korean military finds her.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = Episode 2\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|15}}\n |ShortSummary    = After talking Jeong Hyeok and his comrades into hiding her in his home, Se-ri gets a taste of his way of life. Gu Seung-jun buys refuge in a secluded villa in North Korea through a broker.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = Episode 3\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Se-ri was discovered hiding at Jeong Hyeok's home during an unexpected home inspection. Jeong Hyeok invents a bold background story for Se-ri as a recently-returned agent from Division 11, the secret division of North Korean military which has spys sent to South Korea. He calls Se-ri his fiance, in his attempt to protect her. However, his rival, Cho Cheol Gang isn't so easy to fool. Seo Dan, Jeong Hyeok's fiance for 10 years, returns to North Korea after finishing her studies in Russia.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = Episode 4\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|22}}\n |ShortSummary    = When her escape plan falls through, Se-ri turns to another idea for a way out. Dan heads to the village to see Jeong Hyeok. The villagers are confused on seeing Dan, as they think that Se-ri is Jeong Hyeok's fiance. \n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = Episode 5\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|28}}\n |ShortSummary    = Jeong Hyeok agrees to marry Dan sooner, as his parents wish, but they must do him a favor first. Seung-jun catches a glimpse of Se-ri.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = Episode 6\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|29}}\n |ShortSummary    = Dan is less than happy when she hears Jeong Hyeok and Se-ri are at a hotel together. Meanwhile, Seung-jun plays what cards he has to save himself.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = Episode 7\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|01|11}}\n |ShortSummary    = A flight out of North Korea awaits Se-ri at the airport. But unwilling to leave Jeong Hyeok while he's injured, she brings him to the hospital instead, thus missing her flight out of North Korea.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = Episode 8\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|01|12}}\n |ShortSummary    = Keeping Jeong Hyeok away from Se-ri turns out to be much more difficult than Seung-jun anticipated. Cheol Gang stays on their tail.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = Episode 9\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|01|18}}\n |ShortSummary    = Se-ri faces her kidnapper. Elsewhere, Jeong Hyeok is forced to spread a formidable rumor about himself in order to escape Cheol Gang's clutches.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Episode 10\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|01|19}}\n |ShortSummary    = Back to her cushy life in the spotlight, Se-ri takes care of business \u2014 though nothing feels quite the same. Jeong Hyeok goes after Cheol Gang in South Korea, who in turn is after Se-Ri to use her to blackmail Jeong-hyeok's family.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 11\n |Title           = Episode 11\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|02|01}}\n |ShortSummary    = It is Jeong Hyeok's turn to adjust to a new world. Back in North Korea, Dan gives Seung-jun a place to stay after he loses his protection.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 12\n |Title           = Episode 12\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|02|02}}\n |ShortSummary    = Hoping to meet Jeong Hyeok, his comrades attend an event hosted by Se-ri's company. Seung-jun opens up to Dan over a bowl of rice porridge.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 13\n |Title           = Episode 13\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|02|08}}\n |ShortSummary    = Se-ri sends the comrades on a shopping spree, and plays hooky from work with Jeong Hyeok. Jung Man Bok encounters a dilemma.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 14\n |Title           = Episode 14\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|02|09}}\n |ShortSummary    = While Jeong Hyeok keeps watch over Se-ri, his comrades make themselves useful. Seung-jun can't stop worrying about Dan.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 15\n |Title           = Episode 15\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|02|15}}\n |ShortSummary    = South Korean officials try to figure out what's going on, but they're given conflicting stories. Seung-jun flees from his captors.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 16\n |Title           = Episode 16\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|02|16}}\n |ShortSummary    = Before departing, Jeong Hyeok leaves behind a surprise that keeps on giving messages from Jeong Hyeok's phone everyday. The last message tells Se-ri where to find Jeong Hyeok. Dan delivers bittersweet justice.\n |LineColor       = 8B008B\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nThe premise of ''Crash Landing on You'' was inspired by a real event involving South Korean actress, Jung Yang.<ref name=seven/><ref name=glimpse>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/s-korean-drama-offers-glimpse-of-daily-life-in-north-korea|title=South Korean drama Crash Landing On You offers glimpse of daily life in North Korea|accessdate=February 29, 2020|last=Choon|first=Chang May|date=February 29, 2020|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]}}</ref> In September 2008, Yang and three others had to be rescued after bad fog had caused their leisure boat to drift \"into the maritime boundary between North and South Korea.\"<ref name=rescued>{{cite web|url=https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=30980|title=Boat Carrying Actress Rescued Near Border|accessdate=February 29, 2020|last=Choon|first=Chang May|date=September 12, 2008|publisher=[[The Korea Times]]}}</ref> [[Park Ji-eun]], the drama's [[screenwriter]], was introduced to [[North Korean defectors|North Korean defector]] turned film adviser and writer Kwak Moon-wan, who became part of the drama's writing team.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/crash-landing-on-you-korean-drama-crosses-the-north-south-divide-132140|title=Crash Landing on You: Korean drama crosses the north-south divide|last=Son|first=Sarah A.|date=February 25, 2020|website=The Conversation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Kwak, who studied [[Film director|film directing]] in [[Pyongyang]] and had also been a member of an elite security force protecting the [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|Kims]], helped in crafting the drama's plot and in conceptualizing the setting and scenes in the drama portraying North Korean life.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51526625|title=Crash Landing on You: The defector who brought North-South Korean romance to life|last=|first=|date=February 22, 2020|website=[[BBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Filming===\nThe production process proved to be \"painstakingly meticulous\", owing to [[North Korea\u2013South Korea relations|South Korea's relationship with North Korea]] where most of the story's plot ensues.<ref name=abcnews0220>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/cross-border-korean-drama-overcomes-political-risks-69118681|title=Cross-border S Korean drama overcomes political risks|accessdate=February 21, 2020|last=Park|first=Juwon\n|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> The use of the honorific ''Chairman'' to refer to [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|North Korea's leaders]] was avoided, and the [[Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-il badges|North Korean lapel pins]] used by the cast members taking North Korean roles were one third smaller than their actual size.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/cross-border-south-korean-drama-overcomes-political-risks-1.4821987|title=Cross-border South Korean drama overcomes political risks|last=Park|first=Juwon|date=February 21, 2020|website=[[CTV News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> [[Property master|Props manager]] Joo Dong-man said the crew did not have a \"guidebook on multiple hurdles he had to hop over \u2014 skillfully and delicately \u2013 to accurately depict the country while dodging criticism\" and, thus, had to be careful \"not to misrepresent the state\". They worked with guidance from North Koreans living in South Korea and research.<ref name=abcnews0220/><ref name=seven/>\n\nThe first [[Read-through|script reading]] took place on July 31, 2019 in [[Sangam-dong]], Seoul, and filming overseas started at the end of August 2019.<ref name=hearts>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatechdesk.com/k-drama-crash-landing-on-you-on-netflix-international-is-capturing-hearts-eyeballs-worldwide/|title=K-Drama 'Crash Landing on You' on Netflix International is capturing hearts & eyeballs worldwide|accessdate=February 29, 2020|last=Editor|first=|date=January 30, 2020|publisher=KoreaTechDesk}}</ref> North Korean scenes were shot in South Korea and Mongolia.<ref name=seven/> Scenes that took place in Switzerland were shot on location.<ref name=seven/>\n\n==Reception==\n===Audience response===\nEarly in its run, ''Crash Landing on You'' was the fourth highest rated Korean cable drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2019/12/30/local-shows-and-6-underground-most-popular-on-netflix-asia-in-2019|title= Local shows and \"6 Underground\" most popular on Netflix Asia in 2019|work=The Star Malaysia|language=en|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> The final episode's ratings made it the second highest rated Korean drama in cable television history, surpassing fellow [[tvN]] dramas ''[[Reply 1988]]'' and ''[[Guardian: The Lonely and Great God]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=February 9, 2020 Nationwide Cable Ratings|url=https://www.nielsenkorea.co.kr/tv_terrestrial_day.asp?menu=Tit_1&sub_menu=3_1&area=00&begin_date=20200209|website=Nielsen Korea|quote=1st (tvN) \ud1a0\uc77c\ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8(\uc0ac\ub791\uc758\ubd88\uc2dc\ucc29<\ubcf8>) 19.513%}}</ref> \n\nThe show became a phenomenal hit in South Korea, With 1.75 billion online views ''Crash Landing on You'' had outperformed the prior leader for most viewed drama clips, [[Mr. Sunshine]], by 200 million views as of February 17th, 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hancinema.net/hancinema-s-news-crash-landing-on-you-breaks-record-for-online-clip-views-138901.html |title= Crash Landing on You Breaks Record for Online Clip Views |work=Han Cinema |language=Kr|accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\nThe show was also a hit throughout Asia especially in [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], the [[Philippines]], and [[Thailand]] with a-list celebrities in those countries posting pictures on their social media platforms stating that they are currently binge-watching the drama. Some even photoshopped themselves on photos with lead stars [[Hyun Bin]] and [[Son Ye-jin]]. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://th.hellomagazine.com/celebrity-news/celebrity-with-crash-landing-on-you/|title= \u0e2d\u0e34\u0e19\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e21\u0e32\u0e01! \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e48\u0e32\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e40\u0e25\u0e1a\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e19\u0e32\u0e07\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e40\u0e01\u0e32\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e35\u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e07 'Crash Landing on You'|work=Hello Magazine Thailand|language=th|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> The finale was the top trending topic on [[Twitter]] with the hashtag ''#CrashLandingOnYouFinale'' topping the list hours before the episode aired. ''Crash Landing on You'' also emerged as one of the top shows on [[Netflix]] (who owns the distribution rights outside South Korea) and continued to enjoy widespread popularity even after the show has ended.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crash Landing On You tops Netflix list of most-watched content among Filipinos|url=https://latestchika.com/crash-landing-on-you-tops-netflix-list-of-most-watched-content-among-filipinos/|website=Latest Chika|language=en|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> The drama was also an immense success in China. The hashtag for the drama\u2019s final episode has received over 460 million views on China\u2019s Twitter-like\u2014[[Sina Weibo|Weibo]]. The streaming website for the South Korean drama, which holds the copyright in China with Chinese subtitles, crashed on the night it aired the final episode due to the enormous number of users.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1179877.shtml|title= Chinese netizens celebrate love after South Korean drama \u2018Crash Landing On You\u2019 comes to an end |work=Global Times China|language=Chinese|accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===South and North Korea===\nAlthough the series' depiction of North Korea is fictional, it has received praise \"for its portrayal of everyday life in the North, even down to accents and words.\"<ref name=crashes/> It also received positive reviews from [[North Korean defectors]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> A North Korean defector, who had served with the Supreme Guard Command (which protects the ruling Kim family) worked as an adviser for the series, providing the writers with details about life in North Korea as well as North Korean governmental agencies that added credibility to the show.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Subin |title=Crash Landing on You: The defector who brought North-South Korean romance to life |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51526625 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=BBC News World Asia |agency=BBC News Services |date=22 February 2020 |ref=Adviser |language=English |format=Web}}</ref> One of the extras (who portrayed a North Korean villager) is a writer and actress from North Korea who states that she felt \"like [she] was actually back in a North Korean village.\"<ref name=crashes/> Yun Suk-jin, a professor at [[Chungnam National University]], also notes that the series \"changed the stereotypes on North Korea and candidly showed that it too is a place where people live.\"<ref name=crashes>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/cross-border-love-story-crash-landing-on-you-crashes-south-korea-tv-ratings|title=Cross-border love story 'Crash Landing on You' crashes South Korea TV ratings|accessdate=February 16, 2020|last=|first=|date=February 16, 2020|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]}}</ref> Sarah A. Son, Lecturer in Korean Studies at the [[University of Sheffield]] also agrees, noting that ''Crash Landing on You'' responds to the \"socio-cultural divide\" between the North and the South, which academic scholarship cites as one of the biggest obstacles to future unification. Son argues that \"through the re-framing of stereotypes, albeit with some creative licence, ''Crash Landing on You'' arguably humanises the North for its audience in ways that inter-Korean dialogue has not in recent years. Despite its soft-focus romanticisation of the political situation, ''Crash Landing on You'' brings the pain of the division to a personal level for a generation of Koreans who, unlike their grandparents, have no memory of what it was like to be a single nation.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Joanna Elfving-Hwang, associate professor of Korean studies at the [[University of Western Australia]] concurs, stating that \u201cNorth Korea tends to appear in our imagination as the \u2018axis of evil\u2019, we think of [negative things like] nuclear weapons and human rights abuses\u2026this drama has dared to think about North Korean people differently and represented them as quite human and quite Korean.\u201d<ref name=wins>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/lifestyle-culture/article/3074153/crash-landing-you-wins-over-hong-kong-taiwan-fans-being\n|title=Crash Landing on You wins over Hong Kong, Taiwan fans by being more than the usual K-drama love story\n|accessdate=2020-03-08\n|last=Ng\n|first=Naomi\n|date=2020-03-08\n|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]\n}}</ref> Steve Hung Lok-wai, a Korean affairs expert from [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]] states that the drama sidestepped larger political issues through a narrative that did not end with the [[defection]] of either character. Thus, he argues, it's \"quite smart because they avoided all the real taboos but made it believable enough where it would make people think about these political problems.\"<ref name=wins/> John Delury, a professor at [[Yonsei University]], praised the series for its decision to draw parallels between powerful families in both the South and the North, and to humanize North Koreans beyond generic stereotypes.<ref name=chord>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/crash-landing-on-you-the-inter-korean-love-story-touching-a-chord-in-the-south/\n|title=Crash Landing on You: the inter-Korean love story touching a chord in the South\n|accessdate=2020-03-16\n|last=Kim\n|first=Jeongmin\n|date=2020-03-16\n|publisher=[[NK News]]\n}}</ref> \n\nThere were also critical responses to the themes of the drama in both regions. In January 2020, The [[Christian Liberal Party]] (CLP) filed a complaint in South Korea against tvN at the [[Seoul Metropolitan Police Agency]], accusing the network of glamorizing North Korea through this series, in violation of the National Security Law.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dong|first1=Sun-hwa|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/01/688_282408.html|date=January 23, 2020|work=[[The Korea Times]]|title=Drama 'Crash Landing on You' accused of glamorizing North Korea|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cho|first=S.|title=Christian Liberal Party Sues tvN For Glorifying North Korea In \"Crash Landing On You\"|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1379011wpp/christian-liberal-party-sues-tvn-for-glorifying-north-korea-in-crash-landing-on-you|accessdate=February 28, 2020|work=Soompi|date=January 23, 2020|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:\uc131\uba85\uc11c [\ubc18\uad6d\uac00\ub2e8\uccb4\ub97c \ubbf8\ud654\uc2dc\ucf1c \ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d\uc744 \uc120\ub3d9\ud558\ub294 \uc815\ubd80\uc640 \ubc29\uc1a1\uc0ac tvN\uc744 \uaddc\ud0c4\ud55c\ub2e4]|trans-title=Statement [We condemn anti-state organizations and the (Moon Jae-in) government and broadcasting company tvN for glorifying North Korea]|url=http://clparty.kr/bbs/board.php?bo_table=comment&wr_id=65|accessdate=January 24, 2020|work=clparty.kr|publisher=[[Christian Liberal Party]]|date=January 8, 2020|language=ko}}</ref> Then, in March 2020, a few North Korean media outlets criticized unnamed South Korean programs and films that explored relations between North and South Korea. While ''Crash Landing on You'' was not directly mentioned by the media outlets, it was perceived to be among the referenced works. Another is the 2019 film, ''[[Ashfall (film)|Ashfall]],'' although that film was also not directly cited in the articles.<ref name=bbc0320>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-news-from-elsewhere-51740826\n|title=North Korea blasts South's 'insulting' dramas and films\n|accessdate=2020-03-04\n|last=Kang\n|first=Taejun\n|date=2020-03-04\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n}}</ref><ref name=KH0320>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200304000745\n|title=Pyongyang calls fans of hit TV drama \u2018Crash Landing\u2019 \u2018immoral\u2019\n|accessdate=2020-03-04\n|last=Sung-mi\n|first=Ahn\n|date=2020-03-04\n|publisher=[[Korea Herald]]\n}}</ref>\n\n===Commercial impact===\nThe success of the drama helped to boost brand items due to product placement. The lead characters portrayed by [[Hyun Bin]] and [[Son Ye-jin]] ate Gold Olive Chicken, a product which had a 100% sales improvement due to the show.<ref name=seven/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hancinema.net/hancinema-s-news-crash-landing-on-you-boosts-barbecue-chicken-sales-138450.html |title=\"Crash Landing on You\" Boosts Barbecue Chicken Sales|work=HanCinema|language=en|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> There was also an increase in sales of the [[Swarovski]] earrings worn by [[Son Ye-jin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/hancinema-s-news-swarovski-earrings-experience-popularity-boost-thanks-to-crash-landing-on-you-137367.html|title=Swarovski Earrings Experience Popularity Boost Thanks to \"Crash Landing on You\"|work=HanCinema|language=en|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Original soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Crash Landing on You: Original Soundtrack\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = various artists\n| cover        = Crash Landing on You (Original Soundtrack).jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 2019\n| genre        = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length       = \n| language     = {{hlist|[[Korean language|Korean]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| label        = [[Stone Music Entertainment]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n\n===''Crash Landing on You: Original Soundtrack''===\nThe following is the official track list of ''Crash Landing on You: Original Soundtrack''.<ref name=\"tvnost\">{{cite web|url=http://program.tving.com/tvn/cloy/11/Board/View|title=\uc0ac\ub791\uc758 \ubd88\uc2dc\ucc29 OST|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TVN (Asian TV channel)|tvN]]|