{"title_page": "Charles La Trobe", "text_new": "{{short description|English-born Australian colonial administrator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Charles La Trobe\n| office           = Lieutenant-Governor of Victoria\n| order            = 1st\n| office2          = 1st Superintendent of [[Port Phillip District|Port Phillip]]\n| term_start2      = 4 February 1839\n| term_end2        = 14 July 1851\n| governor2        = [[George Gipps]]<br />[[Charles Augustus FitzRoy|Charles FitzRoy]]\n| honorific-suffix = CB \n| image            = Charles La Trobe Portrait.jpg\n| caption          = \n| monarch          = [[Queen Victoria]]\n| successor        = [[Charles Hotham|Sir Charles Hotham]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|Hi 3|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = London, England, [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1875|12|4|1801|3|20|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Alfriston|Litlington]], East Sussex, England, United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland\n| nationality      = British\n| spouse           = Sophie de Montmollin (1835\u20131854)<br />Rose Isabelle de Meuron (1855\u20131875)\n| honorific-prefix = \n| imagesize        = \n| term_start       = 15 July 1851\n| term_end         = 5 May 1854\n| restingplace     = Litlington Church\n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname        = Charles Joseph La Trobe\n| footnotes        = family motto is '''Whoever seeks shall find'''\n}}\n\n'''Charles Joseph La Trobe''', [[Order of the Bath|CB]] (or Latrobe; 20 March 1801{{spaced ndash}}4 December 1875) was appointed in 1839 superintendent of the [[Port Phillip District]] of [[New South Wales]] and, after the establishment in 1851 of the colony of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] (now a state of Australia), he became its first [[Governor of Victoria|lieutenant-governor]].\n\nLa Trobe was a strong supporter of religious, cultural and educational institutions.<ref name=\"Eastwood\">{{Cite book|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/la-trobe-charles-joseph-2334|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Eastwood|first=Jill|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|location=Canberra}}</ref><ref>In his first speech in Melbourne La Trobe declared: \"It will not be by individual aggrandisement, by the possession of numerous flocks and herds, or of costly acres, that we shall secure for the country enduring prosperity and happiness, but by the acquisition and maintenance of sound religious and moral institutions, without which no country can become truly great.\" [http://www.latrobesociety.org.au/latrobe.html \"The C J La Trobe Society - Melbourne Victoria\"]. www.latrobesociety.org.au. Retrieved 2016-09-29</ref> During his time as superintendent and lieutenant-governor he oversaw the establishment of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Melbourne|Botanical Gardens]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbg.vic.gov.au/about-us/our-story|title=Our Story {{!}} About Us {{!}} Royal Botanic Gardens Victoria|last=Ltd|first=August Pty|website=www.rbg.vic.gov.au|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref> and provided leadership and support to the formation of entities such as the [[Melbourne Athenaeum|Mechanic's Institute]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mahistory.org.au/images/Website/pdf/earlyyears/firstcommittee_latrobe.pdf|title=Charles Joseph La Trobe 1801\u20131875|last=Marsden|first=Anne|date=June 2011|website=mahistory.org.au|publisher=The Melbourne Athenaeum Inc.|access-date=29 September 2016}}</ref> the [[Royal Melbourne Hospital]], the [[Royal Melbourne Philharmonic|Royal Philharmonic]], the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/07/11/1057783354261.html|title=The ground of champions gets its turn to take a bow - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mcg.org.au/the-stadium/mcg-history/mcg-150th-birthday|title=MCG 150th Birthday|website=www.mcg.org.au|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref> and the [[University of Melbourne]].<ref name=\"Eastwood\"/>\n\nLa Trobe was the nephew of British architect [[Benjamin Henry Latrobe]].\n\n==Early life==\nCharles La Trobe was born in London, the son of [[Christian Ignatius Latrobe]], a leader of the [[Moravian Church]], from a family of French [[Huguenot]] descent, whose mother was a member of the Moravian Church born in the United States. He was educated in England and later spent time in Switzerland<ref name=ADB>{{cite web |url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A020077b.htm |title=La Trobe, Charles Joseph (1801 - 1875)  |accessdate=2007-07-13 |author=Jill Eastwood |work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Volume 2 |publisher=[[Melbourne University Press|MUP]] |year=1967 |pages=89\u201393}}</ref> and was active in [[mountaineering]]; he made a number of ascents in the [[Alps]] 1824&ndash;26. La Trobe wrote several travel books describing his experiences: ''The Alpenstock: Or Sketches of Swiss Scenery and Manners'' (1829) and ''The Pedestrian: A Summer's Ramble in the Tyrol'' (1832).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/la-trobe-charles-joseph-2334|title=La Trobe, Charles Joseph (1801\u20131875)|last=Eastwood|first=Jill|date=1967|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography at the Australian National University|access-date=24 Jan 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1832 he visited the United States along with Count [[Albert Pourtales]], and in 1834 travelled from [[New Orleans]] to [[Mexico]] with [[Washington Irving]]. He then wrote ''The Rambler in North America'' (1835) and ''The Rambler in Mexico'' (1836).<ref name=DAB>{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Charles Joseph|Last=La Trobe|shortlink=0-dict-biogL.html#latrobe1}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 1835 he married Sophie de Montmollin (1809&ndash;1854) in Berne, Switzerland. Their first child, Agnes Louisa de La Trobe, was born on 2 April 1837 in Switzerland.\n\n==Lieutenant-governor==\nIn 1837 La Trobe was entrusted with a government commission in the [[West Indies]] and reported on the future education of the recently emancipated slaves.\n\nOn 4 February 1839<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchdata.ands.org.au/superintendent-of-the-port-phillip-district/166329|title=Superintendent of the Port Phillip District|access-date=2016-10-04}}</ref> he was appointed superintendent of the [[Port Phillip District]] of [[New South Wales]] though he had little managerial and administrative experience. La Trobe sailed into Sydney on 26 July 1839, with his wife and 2-year-old daughter, for training on procedures. The La Trobes went on to Melbourne on 1 October.\n\nLa Trobe bought 12\u00bd acres of land on the fringe of the city, now called [[East Melbourne, Victoria|Jolimont]], at auction at the upset price of \u00a320 an acre; the residents of Melbourne having agreed among themselves not to bid against the superintendent. [[Governor of New South Wales]] [[George Gipps]] was disturbed when he heard about it. La Trobe, however, convinced him that he had acted innocently. On the land he erected his home, which has been preserved and is called [[LaTrobe's Cottage]], which he had transported in sections from London.\n\nMelbourne had a population of around 3,000 at the time and was rapidly expanding{{Citation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source.|date=August 2017}}. La Trobe commenced works to improve sanitation and streets.<ref name=\"DAB\"/> As Port Phillip District was a dependency of New South Wales at the time, all land sales, building plans and officer appointments had to be approved by Gipps, with whom La Trobe had a good personal and working relationship. \n[[File:Agnes Louisa de La Trobe, Madame Pierre de Salis (d.1916) in 1875 (modified_version).jpg|thumbnail|300px|A carte de visite photo of Charles Latrobe's daughter, Agnes Louisa, Madame [[John Francis William, 6th Count de Salis-Soglio#His brother Count Peter|Pierre de Salis]] (1837-1916) in 1875.]]\nA Separation Association had been formed in 1840 wanting Port Phillip District to become a separate colony. In 1841 La Trobe wrote to Gipps, asking him to visit Melbourne to form his own opinion on the separation question.<ref name=\"DAB\"/> La Trobe did not actively campaign for separation, content that [[Earl Grey]] had included separation in the reorganisation plan for the colonies.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> La Trobe acted as lieutenant-governor of [[Van Diemen's Land]] for four months in 1846-47. By 1851, Port Phillip district had gained separation from New South Wales, becoming the colony of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and La Trobe was lieutenant-governor for three years \u2013 a position he held until 1854.\n\nSoon after separation, gold was discovered at several locations in Victoria and La Trobe had to deal with the mass exodus of the population of Melbourne to the gold fields.\n\nHe was commonly referred to as \"Charley Joe\", and by extension, any government officials or policemen were called \"joes\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5UkgUWydJmIC&pg=PA222 Edward Ellis Morris, ''Austral English: A Dictionary of Australasian Words, Phrases and Usages'']</ref> La Trobe, who had suffered self-doubt and criticisms due to his inexperience, submitted his resignation in December 1852 but had to wait until a replacement, [[Charles Hotham]], could take his place.\n\n==After Victoria==\nTowards the end of his governorship, La Trobe's wife Sophie became ill and returned to Europe with their four children. Sophie died on 30 January 1854. On his return to Europe after his term, La Trobe in 1855 married Sophie's sister, Rose Isabelle de Meuron (1821\u20131883), a marriage which was illegal in English law as incestuous at the time. (See [[Deceased Wife's Sister's Marriage Act 1907]].) The couple had two daughters (born 1856 and 1859) in Switzerland and moved to England in 1861.<ref>[http://latrobefamily.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I1404&tree=mytree Mytree]</ref> He did not receive any further British government appointments. His eyesight was increasingly deteriorating, and he was completely blind for the last years of his life.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} He died in 1875.\n\n==Geelong keys==\nLa Trobe is also linked to the discovery of a minor piece of evidence suggesting early [[Theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia|European exploration of Australia]]. In 1847, at Limeburners' Point near [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Charles La Trobe, a keen amateur geologist, was examining the shells from a lime kiln when a worker showed him a set of five keys that he claimed to have found, subsequently named the [[Geelong Keys]]. La Trobe concluded that, based on their appearance, the keys were dropped onto the beach around 100 to 150 years beforehand (i.e., between 1700 and 1750). In 1977, [[Kenneth McIntyre]] hypothesized they were dropped by Portuguese sailors under the command of [[Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o de Mendon\u00e7a]].<ref>McIntyre, K (1977) ''The Secret Discovery of Australia, Portuguese ventures 200 years before Cook'', p.249-262 Souvenir Press, Menindie {{ISBN|0-285-62303-6}}</ref> Since the keys have long been lost, their exact origin cannot be verified. However, research by Geologists [[Edmund Dwen Gill|Edmund Gill]] and P.F.B. Alsop showed the deposit they were found in was 2330\u20132800 years old, making La Trobe's dating impossible.<ref>Gill, E (1987) \"On the McKiggan Theory of the Geelong keys\" in ''The Mahogany ship. Relic or Legend? Proceedings of the Second Australian Symposium on the Mahogany Ship'' (Ed. Potter, B).p.83-86 Warrnambool Institute Press {{ISBN|0-949759-09-0}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:La trobe memorial plaque.jpg|thumb|300px|Memorial plaque at Cape Otway]]\nMuch of Melbourne's substantial inner-ring [[:Category:Parks in Melbourne|parks and gardens]] can be attributed to La Trobe's foresight in reserving this land.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nMelbourne and Victoria are dotted with things named in honour of La Trobe, including [[La Trobe Financial]] in Melbourne's CBD, [[La Trobe University]] and [[Charles La Trobe College]] in Melbourne's north east, the [[La Trobe Reading Room]] at the [[State Library of Victoria]] on [[La Trobe Street, Melbourne|La Trobe Street]] in the CBD, the federal electorate of [[Division of La Trobe|La Trobe]] in Melbourne's outer east, the [[Latrobe Valley]] in southeastern Victoria, [[Mount LaTrobe]] in [[Wilsons Promontory]] and, in Tasmania, [[Latrobe, Tasmania|Latrobe]] and [[Latrobe Council]].\n\nThere are statues of La Trobe outside the State Library and at La Trobe University's Bundoora campus.  The latter statue is notable for its upside down appearance.\n\nThe family motto of La Trobe is used at La Trobe University for their own motto. The motto in English is \"whoever seeks shall find\".<ref>http://www.latrobe.edu.au/about/history</ref>\n\nThe [[flowering plants]] genus of [[Latrobea]] was named after him<ref>CRC World Dictionary of Plant Names: Common Names, Scientific Names, Volume 2 Pae 1431 By Umberto Quattrocchi</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Melbourne]]\n*[[French Australian]]\n*[[Latrobe nugget]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.latrobesociety.org.au La Trobe Society]\n**[http://latrobesociety.org.au/documents/LaTrobeChronology.pdf Charles Joseph La Trobe: A chronology]\n**[http://www.latrobesociety.org.au/documents/LaTrobeGenealogy.pdf Genealogy of the La Trobe family]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101203090455/http://www.foundingdocs.gov.au/item.asp?sdID=16 Governor La Trobe's Instructions, 11 September 1839]\n*[http://www.onlymelbourne.com.au/melbourne_details.php?id=9381 La Trobe statue at La Trobe University Bundoora]\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/16106|title=La Trobe, Charles Joseph (1801\u20131875)|last=Shaw|first=A. G. L.|year=2004|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/16106|accessdate=22 November 2009}} {{ODNBsub}}\n*{{DNB Cite|wstitle=Latrobe, Charles Joseph}}\n*Family tree in [http://mdz10.bib-bvb.de/~db/bsb00000559/images/index.html?seite=159 ''Genealogisches Handbuch der baltischen Ritterschaften, Estland,  G\u00f6rlitz 1930'']{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|de}}\n*Pictures and texts of [https://web.archive.org/web/20100811220546/http://www3.unil.ch/viatimages/index.php?module=search&projet=viaticalpes#/ouvrage-199 ''The Alpenstock, or sketches of Swiss scenery and manners, 1825-1826'' by Charles Joseph Latrobe can be found in the database VIATIMAGES].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-new | office}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Governor of Victoria|Lieutenant-Governor of Victoria]]\n       | years  = 1851\u20131854}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Charles Hotham|Captain Sir Charles Hotham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Trobe, Charles}}\n[[Category:1801 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from London]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Governors of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Burials in Sussex]]\n[[Category:Colony of Victoria people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant-Governors of Victoria]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian public servants]]\n[[Category:Settlers of Melbourne]]\n[[Category:English mountain climbers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English-born Australian colonial administrator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Charles La Trobe\n| office           = Lieutenant-Governor of Victoria\n| order            = 1st\n| office2          = 1st Superintendent of [[Port Phillip District|Port Phillip]]\n| term_start2      = 4 February 1839\n| term_end2        = 14 July 1851\n| governor2        = [[George Gipps]]<br />[[Charles Augustus FitzRoy|Charles FitzRoy]]\n| honorific-suffix = CB \n| image            = Charles La Trobe Portrait.jpg\n| caption          = \n| monarch          = [[Queen Victoria]]\n| successor        = [[Charles Hotham|Sir Charles Hotham]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1801|3|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = London, England, [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1875|12|4|1801|3|20|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Alfriston|Litlington]], East Sussex, England, United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland\n| nationality      = British\n| spouse           = Sophie de Montmollin (1835\u20131854)<br />Rose Isabelle de Meuron (1855\u20131875)\n| honorific-prefix = \n| imagesize        = \n| term_start       = 15 July 1851\n| term_end         = 5 May 1854\n| restingplace     = Litlington Church\n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname        = Charles Joseph La Trobe\n| footnotes        = family motto is '''Whoever seeks shall find'''\n}}\n\n'''Charles Joseph La Trobe''', [[Order of the Bath|CB]] (or Latrobe; 20 March 1801{{spaced ndash}}4 December 1875) was appointed in 1839 superintendent of the [[Port Phillip District]] of [[New South Wales]] and, after the establishment in 1851 of the colony of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] (now a state of Australia), he became its first [[Governor of Victoria|lieutenant-governor]].\n\nLa Trobe was a strong supporter of religious, cultural and educational institutions.<ref name=\"Eastwood\">{{Cite book|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/la-trobe-charles-joseph-2334|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Eastwood|first=Jill|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|location=Canberra}}</ref><ref>In his first speech in Melbourne La Trobe declared: \"It will not be by individual aggrandisement, by the possession of numerous flocks and herds, or of costly acres, that we shall secure for the country enduring prosperity and happiness, but by the acquisition and maintenance of sound religious and moral institutions, without which no country can become truly great.\" [http://www.latrobesociety.org.au/latrobe.html \"The C J La Trobe Society - Melbourne Victoria\"]. www.latrobesociety.org.au. Retrieved 2016-09-29</ref> During his time as superintendent and lieutenant-governor he oversaw the establishment of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Melbourne|Botanical Gardens]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbg.vic.gov.au/about-us/our-story|title=Our Story {{!}} About Us {{!}} Royal Botanic Gardens Victoria|last=Ltd|first=August Pty|website=www.rbg.vic.gov.au|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref> and provided leadership and support to the formation of entities such as the [[Melbourne Athenaeum|Mechanic's Institute]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mahistory.org.au/images/Website/pdf/earlyyears/firstcommittee_latrobe.pdf|title=Charles Joseph La Trobe 1801\u20131875|last=Marsden|first=Anne|date=June 2011|website=mahistory.org.au|publisher=The Melbourne Athenaeum Inc.|access-date=29 September 2016}}</ref> the [[Royal Melbourne Hospital]], the [[Royal Melbourne Philharmonic|Royal Philharmonic]], the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/07/11/1057783354261.html|title=The ground of champions gets its turn to take a bow - theage.com.au|website=www.theage.com.au|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mcg.org.au/the-stadium/mcg-history/mcg-150th-birthday|title=MCG 150th Birthday|website=www.mcg.org.au|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref> and the [[University of Melbourne]].<ref name=\"Eastwood\"/>\n\nLa Trobe was the nephew of British architect [[Benjamin Henry Latrobe]].\n\n==Early life==\nCharles La Trobe was born in London, the son of [[Christian Ignatius Latrobe]], a leader of the [[Moravian Church]], from a family of French [[Huguenot]] descent, whose mother was a member of the Moravian Church born in the United States. He was educated in England and later spent time in Switzerland<ref name=ADB>{{cite web |url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A020077b.htm |title=La Trobe, Charles Joseph (1801 - 1875)  |accessdate=2007-07-13 |author=Jill Eastwood |work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Volume 2 |publisher=[[Melbourne University Press|MUP]] |year=1967 |pages=89\u201393}}</ref> and was active in [[mountaineering]]; he made a number of ascents in the [[Alps]] 1824&ndash;26. La Trobe wrote several travel books describing his experiences: ''The Alpenstock: Or Sketches of Swiss Scenery and Manners'' (1829) and ''The Pedestrian: A Summer's Ramble in the Tyrol'' (1832).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/la-trobe-charles-joseph-2334|title=La Trobe, Charles Joseph (1801\u20131875)|last=Eastwood|first=Jill|date=1967|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography at the Australian National University|access-date=24 Jan 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1832 he visited the United States along with Count [[Albert Pourtales]], and in 1834 travelled from [[New Orleans]] to [[Mexico]] with [[Washington Irving]]. He then wrote ''The Rambler in North America'' (1835) and ''The Rambler in Mexico'' (1836).<ref name=DAB>{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Charles Joseph|Last=La Trobe|shortlink=0-dict-biogL.html#latrobe1}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 1835 he married Sophie de Montmollin (1809&ndash;1854) in Berne, Switzerland. Their first child, Agnes Louisa de La Trobe, was born on 2 April 1837 in Switzerland.\n\n==Lieutenant-governor==\nIn 1837 La Trobe was entrusted with a government commission in the [[West Indies]] and reported on the future education of the recently emancipated slaves.\n\nOn 4 February 1839<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchdata.ands.org.au/superintendent-of-the-port-phillip-district/166329|title=Superintendent of the Port Phillip District|access-date=2016-10-04}}</ref> he was appointed superintendent of the [[Port Phillip District]] of [[New South Wales]] though he had little managerial and administrative experience. La Trobe sailed into Sydney on 26 July 1839, with his wife and 2-year-old daughter, for training on procedures. The La Trobes went on to Melbourne on 1 October.\n\nLa Trobe bought 12\u00bd acres of land on the fringe of the city, now called [[East Melbourne, Victoria|Jolimont]], at auction at the upset price of \u00a320 an acre; the residents of Melbourne having agreed among themselves not to bid against the superintendent. [[Governor of New South Wales]] [[George Gipps]] was disturbed when he heard about it. La Trobe, however, convinced him that he had acted innocently. On the land he erected his home, which has been preserved and is called [[LaTrobe's Cottage]], which he had transported in sections from London.\n\nMelbourne had a population of around 3,000 at the time and was rapidly expanding{{Citation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source.|date=August 2017}}. La Trobe commenced works to improve sanitation and streets.<ref name=\"DAB\"/> As Port Phillip District was a dependency of New South Wales at the time, all land sales, building plans and officer appointments had to be approved by Gipps, with whom La Trobe had a good personal and working relationship. \n[[File:Agnes Louisa de La Trobe, Madame Pierre de Salis (d.1916) in 1875 (modified_version).jpg|thumbnail|300px|A carte de visite photo of Charles Latrobe's daughter, Agnes Louisa, Madame [[John Francis William, 6th Count de Salis-Soglio#His brother Count Peter|Pierre de Salis]] (1837-1916) in 1875.]]\nA Separation Association had been formed in 1840 wanting Port Phillip District to become a separate colony. In 1841 La Trobe wrote to Gipps, asking him to visit Melbourne to form his own opinion on the separation question.<ref name=\"DAB\"/> La Trobe did not actively campaign for separation, content that [[Earl Grey]] had included separation in the reorganisation plan for the colonies.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> La Trobe acted as lieutenant-governor of [[Van Diemen's Land]] for four months in 1846-47. By 1851, Port Phillip district had gained separation from New South Wales, becoming the colony of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and La Trobe was lieutenant-governor for three years \u2013 a position he held until 1854.\n\nSoon after separation, gold was discovered at several locations in Victoria and La Trobe had to deal with the mass exodus of the population of Melbourne to the gold fields.\n\nHe was commonly referred to as \"Charley Joe\", and by extension, any government officials or policemen were called \"joes\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5UkgUWydJmIC&pg=PA222 Edward Ellis Morris, ''Austral English: A Dictionary of Australasian Words, Phrases and Usages'']</ref> La Trobe, who had suffered self-doubt and criticisms due to his inexperience, submitted his resignation in December 1852 but had to wait until a replacement, [[Charles Hotham]], could take his place.\n\n==After Victoria==\nTowards the end of his governorship, La Trobe's wife Sophie became ill and returned to Europe with their four children. Sophie died on 30 January 1854. On his return to Europe after his term, La Trobe in 1855 married Sophie's sister, Rose Isabelle de Meuron (1821\u20131883), a marriage which was illegal in English law as incestuous at the time. (See [[Deceased Wife's Sister's Marriage Act 1907]].) The couple had two daughters (born 1856 and 1859) in Switzerland and moved to England in 1861.<ref>[http://latrobefamily.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I1404&tree=mytree Mytree]</ref> He did not receive any further British government appointments. His eyesight was increasingly deteriorating, and he was completely blind for the last years of his life.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} He died in 1875.\n\n==Geelong keys==\nLa Trobe is also linked to the discovery of a minor piece of evidence suggesting early [[Theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia|European exploration of Australia]]. In 1847, at Limeburners' Point near [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Charles La Trobe, a keen amateur geologist, was examining the shells from a lime kiln when a worker showed him a set of five keys that he claimed to have found, subsequently named the [[Geelong Keys]]. La Trobe concluded that, based on their appearance, the keys were dropped onto the beach around 100 to 150 years beforehand (i.e., between 1700 and 1750). In 1977, [[Kenneth McIntyre]] hypothesized they were dropped by Portuguese sailors under the command of [[Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o de Mendon\u00e7a]].<ref>McIntyre, K (1977) ''The Secret Discovery of Australia, Portuguese ventures 200 years before Cook'', p.249-262 Souvenir Press, Menindie {{ISBN|0-285-62303-6}}</ref> Since the keys have long been lost, their exact origin cannot be verified. However, research by Geologists [[Edmund Dwen Gill|Edmund Gill]] and P.F.B. Alsop showed the deposit they were found in was 2330\u20132800 years old, making La Trobe's dating impossible.<ref>Gill, E (1987) \"On the McKiggan Theory of the Geelong keys\" in ''The Mahogany ship. Relic or Legend? Proceedings of the Second Australian Symposium on the Mahogany Ship'' (Ed. Potter, B).p.83-86 Warrnambool Institute Press {{ISBN|0-949759-09-0}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:La trobe memorial plaque.jpg|thumb|300px|Memorial plaque at Cape Otway]]\nMuch of Melbourne's substantial inner-ring [[:Category:Parks in Melbourne|parks and gardens]] can be attributed to La Trobe's foresight in reserving this land.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nMelbourne and Victoria are dotted with things named in honour of La Trobe, including [[La Trobe Financial]] in Melbourne's CBD, [[La Trobe University]] and [[Charles La Trobe College]] in Melbourne's north east, the [[La Trobe Reading Room]] at the [[State Library of Victoria]] on [[La Trobe Street, Melbourne|La Trobe Street]] in the CBD, the federal electorate of [[Division of La Trobe|La Trobe]] in Melbourne's outer east, the [[Latrobe Valley]] in southeastern Victoria, [[Mount LaTrobe]] in [[Wilsons Promontory]] and, in Tasmania, [[Latrobe, Tasmania|Latrobe]] and [[Latrobe Council]].\n\nThere are statues of La Trobe outside the State Library and at La Trobe University's Bundoora campus.  The latter statue is notable for its upside down appearance.\n\nThe family motto of La Trobe is used at La Trobe University for their own motto. The motto in English is \"whoever seeks shall find\".<ref>http://www.latrobe.edu.au/about/history</ref>\n\nThe [[flowering plants]] genus of [[Latrobea]] was named after him<ref>CRC World Dictionary of Plant Names: Common Names, Scientific Names, Volume 2 Pae 1431 By Umberto Quattrocchi</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Melbourne]]\n*[[French Australian]]\n*[[Latrobe nugget]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.latrobesociety.org.au La Trobe Society]\n**[http://latrobesociety.org.au/documents/LaTrobeChronology.pdf Charles Joseph La Trobe: A chronology]\n**[http://www.latrobesociety.org.au/documents/LaTrobeGenealogy.pdf Genealogy of the La Trobe family]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101203090455/http://www.foundingdocs.gov.au/item.asp?sdID=16 Governor La Trobe's Instructions, 11 September 1839]\n*[http://www.onlymelbourne.com.au/melbourne_details.php?id=9381 La Trobe statue at La Trobe University Bundoora]\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/16106|title=La Trobe, Charles Joseph (1801\u20131875)|last=Shaw|first=A. G. L.|year=2004|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/16106|accessdate=22 November 2009}} {{ODNBsub}}\n*{{DNB Cite|wstitle=Latrobe, Charles Joseph}}\n*Family tree in [http://mdz10.bib-bvb.de/~db/bsb00000559/images/index.html?seite=159 ''Genealogisches Handbuch der baltischen Ritterschaften, Estland,  G\u00f6rlitz 1930'']{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|de}}\n*Pictures and texts of [https://web.archive.org/web/20100811220546/http://www3.unil.ch/viatimages/index.php?module=search&projet=viaticalpes#/ouvrage-199 ''The Alpenstock, or sketches of Swiss scenery and manners, 1825-1826'' by Charles Joseph Latrobe can be found in the database VIATIMAGES].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-new | office}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Governor of Victoria|Lieutenant-Governor of Victoria]]\n       | years  = 1851\u20131854}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Charles Hotham|Captain Sir Charles Hotham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Trobe, Charles}}\n[[Category:1801 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from London]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Governors of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Burials in Sussex]]\n[[Category:Colony of Victoria people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant-Governors of Victoria]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian public servants]]\n[[Category:Settlers of Melbourne]]\n[[Category:English mountain climbers]]\n", "name_user": "1.129.107.164", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_La_Trobe"}
{"title_page": "Paul Deman", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{for|the literary critic|Paul de Man}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Paul Deman\n| image         = 27-7-13 Tour de France Deman.JPG\n| caption       = Deman at the [[1913 Tour de France]]\n| fullname      = Paul Deman\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1889|4|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rekkem]], West Flanders, Belgium\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1961|7|31|1889|4|25|df=y}}\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = [[Tour of Flanders]] (1913)<br>[[Bordeaux\u2013Paris]] (1914)<br>[[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] (1920)<br>[[Paris\u2013Tours]] (1923)\n}}\n'''Paul Deman''' (25 April 1889 in [[Rekkem]], West Flanders, Belgium \u2013 31 July 1961 in [[Outrijve]], Belgium)<ref name=\"CyclingWeb\">[http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8698 The Cycling Website, Rider database, Paul Deman] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727113247/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8698 |date=27 July 2011 }}</ref> was a Belgian professional [[road bicycle racer]] for 15 years from 1909\u20131924, and a carpet maker by trade.<ref name=\"Deman 1\">[http://cyclingart.blogspot.com/2008_01_01_archive.html CyclingArt. History archives, Wednesday, January 16, 2008, Article - Secret agent man]</ref>\n\nHe won the first [[Tour of Flanders]] race in 1913 at the age of 25, defeating a field of 37 riders over a 330&nbsp;km course that ended with 4 laps of the wooden track around a small pond at [[Mariakerke (East Flanders)|Mariakerke]], the suburb of [[Ghent]].<ref name=\"Deman 1\"/> He won the gruelling 592&nbsp;km [[Bordeaux\u2013Paris]] in 1914.<ref name=\"Deman 1\"/> His career almost ended with the [[World War I|first world war]]. He joined Belgium's espionage service and smuggled documents by bike into the neutral [[Netherlands]]. After many trips he was arrested by the Germans and jailed in [[Leuven]] ready to be shot. The [[Armistice]] saved him. He started racing again and won [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] in 1920 and [[Paris\u2013Tours]] in 1923.<ref name=\"Deman 1\"/><ref>Schroeders, Fer (1999), Les Classiques du 20\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle, De Eeclonaar, Belgium, {{ISBN|90-74128-58-0}}, p146</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|8698|Paul Deman}}\n\n{{Tour of Flanders winners}}\n{{Paris\u2013Roubaix winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deman, Paul}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Menen]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from West Flanders]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the literary critic|Paul de Man}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Paul Deman\n| image         = 27-7-13 Tour de France Deman.JPG\n| caption       = Deman at the [[1913 Tour de France]]\n| fullname      = Paul Deman\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1889|4|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rekkem]], West Flanders, Belgium\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1961|7|31|1889|4|25|df=y}}\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = [[Tour of Flanders]] (1913)<br>[[Bordeaux\u2013Paris]] (1914)<br>[[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] (1920)<br>[[Paris\u2013Tours]] (1923)\n}}\n'''Paul Deman''' (25 April 1889 in [[Rekkem]], West Flanders, Belgium \u2013 31 July 1961 in [[Outrijve]], Belgium)<ref name=\"CyclingWeb\">[http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8698 The Cycling Website, Rider database, Paul Deman] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727113247/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8698 |date=27 July 2011 }}</ref> was a Belgian professional [[road bicycle racer]] for 15 years from 1909\u20131924, and a carpet maker by trade.<ref name=\"Deman 1\">[http://cyclingart.blogspot.com/2008_01_01_archive.html CyclingArt. History archives, Wednesday, January 16, 2008, Article - Secret agent man]</ref>\n\nHe won the first [[Tour of Flanders]] race in 1913 at the age of 25, defeating a field of 37 riders over a 330&nbsp;km course that ended with 4 laps of the wooden track around a small pond at [[Mariakerke (East Flanders)|Mariakerke]], the suburb of [[Ghent]].<ref name=\"Deman 1\"/> He won the gruelling 592&nbsp;km [[Bordeaux\u2013Paris]] in 1914.<ref name=\"Deman 1\"/> His career almost ended with the [[World War I|first world war]]. He joined Belgium's espionage service and smuggled documents by bike into the neutral [[Netherlands]]. After many trips he was arrested by the Germans and jailed in [[Leuven]] ready to be shot. The [[Armistice]] saved him. He started racing again and won [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] in 1920 and [[Paris\u2013Tours]] in 1923.<ref name=\"Deman 1\"/><ref>Schroeders, Fer (1999), Les Classiques du 20\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle, De Eeclonaar, Belgium, {{ISBN|90-74128-58-0}}, p146</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|8698|Paul Deman}}\n\n{{Tour of Flanders winners}}\n{{Paris\u2013Roubaix winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deman, Paul}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Menen]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from West Flanders]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Deman"}
{"title_page": "Peter Coyote", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, voice actor, and director}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Peter Coyote at Durell Vineyard, Sonoma, April 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 187px\n| caption = Coyote in April 2019\n| birth_name=Robert Peter Cohon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1941|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Sebastopol, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = actor, author, director, screenwriter, narrator\n| years_active = 1967\u2013present\n| alma_mater = [[Grinnell College]], B.A. 1964<br>[[San Francisco State University]]\n| partner   = Eileen Ewing (1965-1972)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Marilyn McCann|1975|1998|reason=divorced}}{{marriage|Stefanie Pleet|1998|2015|reason=divorced}}\n| children= 2\n| website = [http://www.petercoyote.com Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Peter Coyote''' (born '''Robert Peter Cohon'''; October 10, 1941) is an American actor, author, director, screenwriter and narrator of films, theatre, television and [[audiobook]]s. He is known for his work in various films such as ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982), ''[[Cross Creek (film)|Cross Creek]]'' (1983), ''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]'' (1985), ''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998), ''[[Erin Brockovich (film)|Erin Brockovich]]'' (2000), ''[[A Walk to Remember]]'' (2002), ''[[Hemingway & Gellhorn]]'' (2012) and ''[[Good Kill]]'' (2014). He was also known as the \"Voice of Oscar\" for the [[72nd Academy Awards]] ceremony, the first [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] announcer to be seen on-camera.\n\nCoyote's voice work includes his narration for the opening ceremony of the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iPad]] Retina Display campaign. He narrated the [[PBS]] series ''[[The Pacific Century]]'' (1992), winning an [[Emmy Award|Emmy]], and eight documentaries directed or produced by [[Ken Burns]]: ''[[The West (miniseries)|The West]]'' (1996), ''[[The National Parks: America's Best Idea]]'' (2009), ''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]]'' (2011), ''[[The Dust Bowl (miniseries)|The Dust Bowl]]'' (2012), ''[[The Roosevelts (miniseries)|The Roosevelts: An Intimate History]]'' (2014), ''[[The Vietnam War (TV series)|The Vietnam War]]'' (2017), ''The [[Mayo Clinic]]: Faith--Hope--Science'' (2018), and ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]] (2019). ''He won a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator]] in 2015 for his work on ''The Roosevelts''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/peter-coyote|title=Peter Coyote|website=Emmys.com|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref> His voice has often been said to resemble that of actor [[Henry Fonda]].\n\nCoyote was one of the founders of the [[Diggers (theater)|Diggers]], an [[anarchism|anarchist]] [[Improvisational theatre|improv group]] active in [[Haight-Ashbury]] during the mid-1960s. Coyote was also an actor, writer and director with the [[San Francisco Mime Troupe]]; his prominence in the San Francisco [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] scene led to his being interviewed for the book ''Voices from the Love Generation''. He acted in and directed the first cross-country tour of ''The Minstrel Show'', and his play ''Olive Pits'', co-authored with Mime Troupe member [[Peter Berg (bioregionalist)|Peter Berg]], won the troupe an [[Obie Award]] from ''[[The Village Voice]]''. Coyote became a member, and later chairman, of the [[California Arts Council]] from 1975 to 1983. In the late 1970s, he shifted from acting on stage to acting in [[film]]s. In the 1990s and 2000s (decade), he acted in several television shows. He speaks fluent [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[French language|French]].\n\n==Early life==\nCoyote was born in [[New York City]], the son of Ruth (n\u00e9e Fidler) and Morris Cohon, an investment banker.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/23/Peter-Coyote.html |title=Peter Coyote profile at Film Reference.com |publisher=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307142509/http://www.filmreference.com/film/23/Peter-Coyote.html |archivedate=March 7, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> His father was of [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic Jewish]] descent and his mother came from a working-class [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi Jewish]] family. Her father, trained as a [[rabbi]] in Russia, escaped being drafted into the [[Imperial Russian Army]], and eventually ran a small candy store in [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"family\"/> Coyote \"was raised in a highly intellectual, cultural but unreligious family\",<ref name=\"family\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/7741/edition_id/147/format/html/displaystory.html |title=Peter Coyote: 'an outsider with a Jewish sense of humor' |publisher=Jewishsf.com |date=1998-01-09 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430064121/http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/7741/edition_id/147/format/html/displaystory.html |archivedate=April 30, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> involved in left-wing politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/32919/format/html/displaystory.html |title='&#39;Tie Dayenu'&#39; |publisher=Jewishsf.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410075408/http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/32919/format/html/displaystory.html |archivedate=April 10, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He grew up in [[Englewood, New Jersey]]<ref>[http://www.jackmagazine.com/issue4/petercoyotebio.html Peter Coyote biodata] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906111248/http://www.jackmagazine.com/issue4/petercoyotebio.html |date=September 6, 2008 }}, ''[[Jack Magazine]]''. Accessed November 25, 2007. \"At fourteen he was a campaign worker in the [[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]] presidential campaign in his home town of Englewood New Jersey.\"</ref> and graduated from [[Dwight Morrow High School]] there in 1960. Coyote later said that he was \"half black and half white inside\" due to the strong influence of Susie Nelson, his family's [[African Americans|African-American]] housekeeper.<ref>[http://www.hendersondispatch.com/index.php?pSetup=hendersondailydispatch&curDate=20080429&pageToLoad=showFreeArticle.php&type=art&index=01 \"Susie Nelson's other son\" by Al Wheless, ''[[The Daily Dispatch]]'', [[Henderson, North Carolina]], April 29, 2008]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> Coyote is the maternal uncle of prominent librarian [[Jessamyn West (librarian)|Jessamyn West]].\n\nWhile a student at [[Grinnell College]] in 1961, Coyote was one of the organizers of a group of twelve students who traveled to Washington, D.C. during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] supporting President [[John F. Kennedy]]'s \"peace race\". Kennedy invited the group into the [[White House]], the first time protesters had ever been so recognized, and they met for several hours with [[McGeorge Bundy]]. The group received wide press coverage. They [[mimeograph]]ed the resulting headlines and sent them to every college in the United States.<ref name=\"bio\"/> He was also in a band called the Kittatinny Mountain Boys. Referenced in The Rainman's Third Cure by Peter Coyote.<ref name=\"Coyote2015\">{{cite book|author=Peter Coyote|title=The Rainman's Third Cure: An Irregular Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ma32BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA108|date=1 April 2015|publisher=Catapult|isbn=978-1-61902-635-3|pages=108\u2013}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nOnce he graduated from Grinnell with a BA in English literature in 1964,<ref name=\"bio\"/> he moved to the [[West Coast of the United States|west coast]], despite having been accepted at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]],<ref name=\"bio\"/> and commenced working towards a master's degree in [[creative writing]] at [[San Francisco State University]].<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n===Name change===\nWhile still at Grinnell, Coyote ingested [[peyote]] and had a hallucination in which he saw his footprints as [[coyote]] paw-prints. A few years later, he came across ''Coyote's Journal'', a poetry magazine, and recognized its logo as the same paw-prints he had seen during his drug-induced experience. This caused him to change his name to Coyote, after meeting [[Rolling Thunder (person)|Rolling Thunder]] (John Pope), a self-styled [[Shamanism|shaman]], who believed the experience was spiritually significant.<ref>\"Krassner reviews 'Sleeping Where I Fall' by Peter Coyote\" (Sep/Oct 1999) ''[[Tikkun (magazine)|Tikkun]]'' Vol.14 No.5 pp. 71-74</ref>\n\n==Countercultural activities==\nAfter a short apprenticeship at the San Francisco [[Actor's Workshop]], he joined the [[San Francisco Mime Troupe]], a radical political street theater whose members were arrested for performing in parks without permits. Coyote acted, wrote scripts, and directed in the Mime Troupe. Coyote directed the first cross-country tour of ''The Minstrel Show, Civil Rights in a Cracker Barrel,''<ref name=\"bio\"/> a controversial play closed by authorities in several cities.<ref>\"Mime Troupe Gets Injunction, Acclaim\" (6 Feb 1968) ''Los Angeles Times''</ref>\n\nFrom 1967 to 1975, Coyote was a prominent member of the San Francisco Haight-Ashbury [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] community and a founding member, along with [[Emmett Grogan]], Peter Berg, Judy Goldhaft, Kent Minault, Nina Blasenheim, David Simpson, Jane Lapiner, and Billy Murcott, of the [[Diggers (theater)|Diggers]], an anarchist group known for operating anonymously and without money.<ref name=\"diggers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diggers.org/overview.htm |title=Overview: who were (are) the Diggers? |publisher=Diggers.org |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> They created provocative \"theater\" events designed to heighten awareness of problems associated with the notion of private property, consumerism, and identification with one's work. They fed nearly 600 people a day for \"free\", asking only that people pass through a six-foot by six-foot square known as The Free Frame of Reference. They ran a Free Store,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diggers.org/free_store.htm |title=Digger Virtual Free Store |publisher=Diggers.org |date=1967-10-14 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170248/http://www.diggers.org/free_store.htm |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"thesun\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issues/426/against_the_grain |title=Against The Grain: Peter Coyote On Buddhism, Capitalism, And The Enduring Legacy Of The Sixties |author=David Kupfer |journal=[[The Sun (magazine)|The Sun]] |issue=426 |accessdate=May 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419234605/http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issues/426/against_the_grain |archivedate=April 19, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> (where not only the goods, but the management roles were free), a Free Medical Clinic, and even a short-lived Free Bank.<ref name=\"diggers\"/> The Diggers evolved into a group known as the Free Family, which established chains of communes around the [[Pacific Northwest]] and [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]]. Coyote was the best known resident of the [[Black Bear Ranch]] commune in [[Siskiyou County, California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diggers.org/freefall/elsa.html |title=The Free-Fall Chronicles: Elsa's Story |publisher=Diggers.org |date=1996-06-08 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303192835/http://www.diggers.org/freefall/elsa.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe was a friend of [[Rolling Thunder (person)|Rolling Thunder]], a purported Shoshone Medicine man. He has also been a friend of [[Leonard Peltier]], a Native American activist and member of the [[American Indian Movement]] (AIM) since the 1960s and, along with author [[Peter Mathiessen]], is one of Peltier's two non-native advisers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/chepesiuk1.html |title=Hollywood Radical |publisher=Peter Coyote |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172300/http://www.petercoyote.com/chepesiuk1.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOf this period of his life, Coyote wrote in ''Sleeping Where I Fall,'' <blockquote>The failure to curb personal indulgence was a major collective error. Our journeys down the path along with [[Paul Verlaine|Verlaine]] and [[Arthur Rimbaud|Rimbaud]], disordered our senses, senselessly wasted young lives, and often sabotaged what we labored so diligently to construct. ... It is the artist's responsibility to manifest sanity and health\u2014something we did not fully understand.<ref>Peter Coyote (1998) ''Sleeping Where I Fall: A Chronicle,'' Counterpoint Press, Berkeley, California {{ISBN|1-58243-011-X}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Discovering Zen==\nCoyote had first discovered [[Zen]] in his teens via the works of [[Jack Kerouac]], [[Gary Snyder]], and other [[Beat Generation|Beats]]. Coyote met Snyder with the Diggers and was impressed with Snyder's \"gravitas and elegance, his care and deliberation\".<ref name=\"thesun\"/><ref name=\"sweep\">{{cite interview |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/sweepingzen.html |title=Peter Hosho Jishi Coyote |interviewer=Sweeping Zen |date=June 16, 2008 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013171201/http://petercoyote.com/sweepingzen.html |archivedate=October 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1975, Coyote undertook meditation practice and eventually became a dedicated practitioner of American Zen Buddhism, moving into the [[San Francisco Zen Center]].<ref name=\"sweep\"/><ref name=\"zenbones\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petercoyote.com/zenflesh.html |title=Zen Flesh, Zen Bones |publisher=Petercoyote.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> He was later ordained a lay priest in the [[S\u014dt\u014d]] tradition and was ordained as a Zen Priest in 2015.<ref name=\"sweep\"/><ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Peter Coyote lay ordained in Mill Valley, CA | url=http://www.cuke.com/sangha_news/coyote%20ordain.html | work=Cuke Sangha News | date=April 22, 2007 | accessdate=June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Joyce Kleiner |title=Coyote reflects on wild dogs and the next 1,000 years |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/millvalley021512.html |work=The Mill Valley Herald |date=February 15, 2012 |accessdate=May 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nCoyote performed [[audiobook]] recordings of [[Shunryu Suzuki]]'s ''[[Zen Mind, Beginner's Mind]]'', [[Paul Reps]]'s ''[[Zen Flesh, Zen Bones]]'' as well as narrating the documentary ''Inquiry into the Great Matter: A History of Zen Buddhism''.<ref name=\"zenbones\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofzendvd.com |title=''Inquiry into the Great Matter: A History of Zen Buddhism'' |accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== San Francisco Arts Commission and the California Arts Council ==\nIn keeping with his dedication to community-based art, Peter Coyote was employed in the early 1970s by the [[San Francisco Arts Commission]] in the historical Neighborhood Arts Program (NAP), with funding from the [[Comprehensive Employment and Training Act]] (CETA, Pub.L. 93\u2013203), a United States federal law enacted by Congress, signed into law by President Richard Nixon in 1973, to train workers and provide them with jobs in the public service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/R?d095:FLD001:@4(Manpower+training+programs) |title=Manpower training programs, The Library of Congress |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> The San Francisco Arts Commission's Neighborhood Arts/CETA Program was the first in the country to use CETA funds to hire artists to work in service to a city.<ref>{{YouTube|O8awBsmvtnc}}</ref> From this position, Coyote was appointed by [[Jerry Brown|Governor Jerry Brown]] to be a member of the [[California Arts Council]], the state agency which determines art policy for the state. He served on the CAC from 1975 to 1983. After his first year, Coyote was elected chairman by his peers three years in a row. During his tenure as chairman, the Council's overhead expenses dropped from 50% to 15%, the lowest in the State, and the Arts Council budget rose from $1 million to $16 million. His council introduced the idea of artists as \"creative problem solvers.\" By paying artists to \"solve problems for the state\" rather than to make art, they bypassed the objections of many conservative lawmakers. Coyote engineered relationships with 14 departments of the State of California, which began to use artists in a variety of capacities, paying 50 cents on the dollar for it. The policy and the council were an immense success, giving Coyote the confidence (after 12 years in the counterculture) to try his hand at mainstream film-acting.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\n==Film and television acting==\nIn 1978, Coyote began acting again (\"to shake the rust out\") appearing in plays at San Francisco's award-winning [[Magic Theatre]]. While playing the lead in the world premiere of [[Sam Shepard]]'s ''[[True West (play)|True West]]'', a Hollywood agent approached him, and his film career began with ''[[Die Laughing (film)|Die Laughing]]'' (1980). He gave supporting performances in ''[[Tell Me a Riddle (film)|Tell Me a Riddle]]'' (1980), ''[[Southern Comfort (1981 film)|Southern Comfort]]'' (1981) and as the mysterious scientist \"Keys\" in ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982). He was seriously considered for the role of [[Indiana Jones]] in ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981), and auditioned for the part. Coyote's first starring role was in the science fiction adventure ''[[Timerider: The Adventure of Lyle Swann]]'' (1982). He also starred in ''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]'' (1985) and ''[[Outrageous Fortune (film)|Outrageous Fortune]]'' (1987). Since then, he has made more than 120 films for theaters and television and has played starring roles for many directors, including [[Roman Polanski]] (''[[Bitter Moon]]''), [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]] (''[[Kika (1993 film)|Kika]]''), [[Martin Ritt]] (''[[Cross Creek (film)|Cross Creek]]''), [[Jean-Paul Rappeneau]] (''[[Bon Voyage (2003 film)|Bon Voyage]]''), [[Diane Kurys]] (''[[A Man in Love (1987 film)|A Man in Love]]'') and [[Walter Salles]] (''[[A Grande Arte|Exposure]]''). For his 1990 guest appearance on the television series ''[[Road to Avonlea]]'', he received his first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination.\n\n[[Leonard Maltin]] once wrote, \"Coyote's no rubber-stamp leading man\", but he seems comfortable with that. \"I'm a [[Zen]] Buddhist student first, actor second\", Coyote has said. \"If I can't reconcile the two lives, I'll stop acting. I spend more time off-screen than on.\" In addition to his movie work in more recent films such as ''[[Sphere (1998 film)|Sphere]]'', ''[[A Walk to Remember]]'', and ''[[Erin Brockovich (film)|Erin Brockovich]]'', Coyote has also appeared in many made-for-TV movies and miniseries, and he does commercial voice-overs. Coyote was cast in lead roles on several television series: ''[[The 4400]]'' in 2004 and ''[[The Inside (TV series)|The Inside]]'' in 2005. After ''The Inside'' was canceled, Coyote returned to ''The 4400'' as a special guest star for their two-part season finale, then joined the cast of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s series ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'' as the [[Vice President of the United States]], and the next year did a four episode turn as [[Sally Field]]'s disreputable boyfriend in ''[[Brothers & Sisters (2006 TV series)|Brothers & Sisters]]''.\n\n==Narration==\nIn 2005, Coyote served as the narrator for several prominent projects including the documentary film ''[[Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room]]'' and the ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]''-produced [[PBS]] documentary based on [[Jared Diamond]]'s ''[[Guns, Germs, and Steel]]''. He also narrated an episode of the series ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' in April 2006. In 2008, he narrated ''[[Torturing Democracy]]'', a documentary produced by [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] which details the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush administration]]'s use of \"[[enhanced interrogation techniques]]\" in the [[War on Terror]]. He also narrated the 12-hour [[Ken Burns]] series on the [[The National Parks: America's Best Idea|National Parks]], and 15 episodes for the ''[[National Geographic Explorer]]'' series. In 2010 he narrated the documentary ''Solitary Confinement'' on the effect of long-term isolation, with footage taken from [[Colorado State Penitentiary]] where all prisoners are held this way. In 2014, he appeared in the [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] television series ''[[Perception (American TV series)|Perception]]'', as the father of the main character, Dr. Daniel Pierce, and narrated Burns' [[The Roosevelts (miniseries)|''The Roosevelts: An Intimate History'']]; the latter saw him win his first [[Primetime Emmy Award]]. In 2019, he narrated Burns' PBS documentary ''[[Country Music (miniseries)]]''.<ref>https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nCoyote's [[left-wing politics]] are evident in his articles for ''[[Mother Jones magazine|Mother Jones]]'' magazine, some of which he wrote as a delegate to the [[1996 Democratic National Convention]]; in his disagreements with [[David Horowitz (conservative writer)|David Horowitz]]; and in his autobiography ''Sleeping Where I Fall''. In 2006, he developed a political television show for [[Link TV]] called \"The Active Opposition\" and in 2007 created ''Outside the Box with Peter Coyote'' starting on Link TV's special, Special: ''The End of Oil \u2013 Part 2''.\n\nMany of Coyote's stories from the 1967 to 1975 [[counter-culture]] period are included in his memoir, ''Sleeping Where I Fall,'' published by [[Counterpoint Press]] in April 1998. One of the stories incorporated into his book is \"Carla's Story,\" about a 16-year-old mother who lived communally with Coyote, and who, after learning of her husband's murder, became a drug addict, then a prostitute, had her children stolen, and continued to spiral downhill until she turned her life around. This story was published in ''[[Zyzzyva (magazine)|Zyzzyva]]'', and awarded the 1993\u20131994 [[Pushcart Prize]]. He also states he was a close friend of singer [[Janis Joplin]]. Coyote has a website,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/ |title=Peter Coyote's website |publisher=Petercoyote.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015012/http://www.petercoyote.com/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> which features the titles of all his movies and extended samples of much of his writing. He is a member at RedRoom.com, a website for authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redroom.com/member/peter-coyote|title=Redroom.com - Earn Money - Save Money - Multiply Money|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302034224/http://redroom.com/member/peter-coyote|archivedate=March 2, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, his memoir ''The Rainman's Third Cure: An Irregular Education'' was released, where he \"provides portraits of mentors that shaped him\u2014including his violent, intimidating father, a bass player, a Mafia Consiglieri, and beat poet Gary Snyder, who introduced him to the practice of Zen.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Coyote's Path From Street Theater To the Big Screen to Zen|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/peter-coyotes-path-street-theater-big-screen-zen/|publisher=[[WNYC]]|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426025851/http://www.wnyc.org/story/peter-coyotes-path-street-theater-big-screen-zen/|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Actor===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n*''[[Alcatraz: The Whole Shocking Story]]'' (1980) as Lt. Micklin \n*''[[Die Laughing (film)|Die Laughing]]'' (1980) as Davis\n*''[[Southern Comfort (1981 film)|Southern Comfort]]'' (1981) as Sergeant Poole\n*''[[Isabel's Choice]]'' (1981 TV film) as Wynn Thomas\n*''[[Timerider: The Adventure of Lyle Swann]]'' (1982) as Porter Reese\n*''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982) as Keys\n*''[[Endangered Species (1982 film)|Endangered Species]]'' (1982) as Steele\n*''[[Strangers Kiss|Strangers' Kiss]]'' (1983) Stanley, the Director\n*''[[Cross Creek (film)|Cross Creek]]'' (1983) as Norton Baskin\n*''[[Slayground]]'' (1983) as Stone \n*''[[Heartbreakers (1984 film)|Heartbreakers]]'' (1984) as Arthur Blue\n*''[[The Legend of Billie Jean]]'' (1985) as Det. Larry Ringwald\n*''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]'' (1985) as Thomas Krasny\n*''[[The Blue Yonder]]'' (1985) as Max Knickerbocker\n*''[[Outrageous Fortune (film)|Outrageous Fortune]]'' (1987) as Michael Sanders\n*''[[A Man in Love (1987 film)|Un homme amoureux]]'' (1987) as Steve Elliott\n*''[[Echoes in the Darkness]]'' (1987 TV mini-series) as William Bradfield Jr.\n*''[[Heart of Midnight (film)|Heart of Midnight]]'' (1988) as Sharpe/Larry\n*''[[The Man Inside (1990 film)|The Man Inside]]'' (1990) as Henry Tobel\n*''[[A Grande Arte]] - American title is Exposure'' (1991) as Mr. Peter Mandrake\n*''[[Keeper of the City]]'' (1991) as Frank Nordhall\n*''[[Road to Avonlea]]'' (1991) as Romney Penhallow\n*''[[Bitter Moon]]'' (1992) as Oscar\n*''[[Kika (1993 film)|Kika]]'' (1993) as Nicholas\n*''[[That Eye, the Sky]]'' (1994) as Henry Warburton\n*''[[Breach of Conduct (film)|Breach of Conduct]]'' (1994) as Col. Andrew Case\n*''[[Moonlight and Valentino]]'' (1995) as Paul\n*''[[Buffalo Girls (TV movie)|Buffalo Girls]]'' (1995) as Buffalo Bill Cody\n*''[[Unforgettable (1996 film)|Unforgettable]]'' (1996) as Don Bresler\n*''[[Murder in My Mind]]'' (1997) as Arthur Lefcourt\n*''[[Road Ends]]'' (1997) as Gene Gere\n*''[[Sphere (1998 film)|Sphere]]'' (1998) as Captain Harold C. Barnes\n*''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998) as Bill Davis\n*''[[Route 9 (film)|Route 9]]'' (1998) as Sheriff Dwayne Hogan\n*''[[Random Hearts]]'' (1999) as Cullen Chandler\n*''[[Execution of Justice]]'' (1999) as [[Harvey Milk]]\n*''[[More Dogs Than Bones]]'' (2000) as Det. Darren Cody\n*''[[Erin Brockovich (film)|Erin Brockovich]]'' (2000) as Kurt Potter\n*''[[Jack the Dog]]'' (2001) as Alfred Stieglitz\n*''[[Midwives (film)|Midwives]]'' (2001) as Stephen Hastings\n*''[[Femme Fatale (2002 film)|Femme Fatale]]'' (2002) as Watts\n*''[[A Walk to Remember]]'' (2002) as Rev. Sullivan\n*''[[Bon Voyage (2003 film)|Bon Voyage]]'' (2003) as Alex Winckler\n*''[[The Hebrew Hammer]]'' (2003) as JJL Chief Bloomenbergensteinenthal\n*''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'' (2004) as [[George Crook|General Crook]]\n*''[[Law & Order: Trial by Jury]]'' (2005) as Mike LaSalle\n*''[[Independent Lens]]'' (2005\u20132009) as Narrator\n*''[[The Inside (TV series)|The Inside]]'' (2005) as Special Agent Webster\n*''[[Deepwater (film)|Deepwater]]'' (2005) as Herman Finch\n*''[[A Little Trip to Heaven]]'' (2005) as Frank\n*''[[Return of the Living Dead: Necropolis]]'' (2005) as Uncle Charles\n*''[[Return of the Living Dead: Rave to the Grave]]'' (2005) as Uncle Charles\n*''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'' (2005\u20132006) as Warren Keaton\n*''[[The 4400]]'' (2004\u20132006) as Dennis Ryland\n*''[[Behind Enemy Lines II: Axis of Evil]]'' (2006) as President Manning\n*''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' (2001\u20132011). Episode aired 15 November 2007, Season 07, Episode 07 as Lionel Shill\n*''[[Brothers & Sisters (2006 TV series)|Brothers & Sisters]]'' (2007) as Mark August\n*''[[Five Dollars a Day]]'' (2008) as Bert Kruger\n*''[[Dr. Dolittle: Tail to the Chief]]'' as President Sterling\n*''[[All Roads Lead Home]]'' (2008) as Hock\n*''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'' (2008) as Ned Quinn\n*''[[The Lena Baker Story]]'' (2008) as Elliot Arthur\n*''[[FlashForward (TV series)|FlashForward]]'' (2009) as President Dave Segovia\n*''[[This Is Not a Movie]]'' (2010) as CEO of Propaganda / screenwriter\n*''[[Last Will (film)|Last Will]]'' (2011) as Judge Garner \n*''The Gundown'' (2011) as Tom Morgan\n*''[[Stage Left (documentary film)|Stage Left: A Story of Theater in the Bay Area]]'' (2011) as Himself\n*''[[La Ran\u00e7on de la gloire]]'' (2014) as John Crooker\n*''[[Good Kill]]'' (2014) as Langley (voice)\n*''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]'' (2015) as Senator McCreary\n*''[[Eva & Leon]]'' (2015) as Le p\u00e8re d'Eva\n*''[[No Deposit]]'' (2015) as Police Chief Williams\n*''[[The Disappearance (2017 TV series)|The Disappearance]]'' (2017) as Henry Sullivan\n*''[[1 Mile to You]]'' (2017) as Prin. Umber\n*''[[A Higher Loyalty (miniseries)|A Higher Loyalty]]'' (TBA) as [[Robert Mueller]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Narrator===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''The UFO Experience'', a TV documentary directed by Ronald K. Lakis in which Coyote appeared and also narrated. (1982)\n*''[[Zen Mind, Beginner's Mind]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Waldo Salt: A Screenwriter's Journey]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Hatchet (novel)|Hatchet]]'' by [[Gary Paulsen]]\n*''The Education of Little Tree'' by [[Asa Earl Carter|Forrest Carter]]\n*''Contrary Warriors''\n*''The Breathtaker'' by [[Alice Blanchard]]\n*''[[The Teachings of Don Juan: A Yaqui Way of Knowledge]]'' by [[Carlos Castaneda]]\n*''National Geographic: Cyclone!'' (1995)\n*''[[The West (1996 film)|The West]]'' Produced by [[Ken Burns]] and directed by [[Stephen Ives]] (1996)\n*''21st Century Jet: The Building of the Boeing 777'' (1996)\n*''Survivors of the Skeleton Coast'' (1997)\n*''Video Justice: Crime Caught on Tape'' (1997)\n*''[[World's Scariest Police Chases]]'' Pilot episode (1997)\n*''The History of Sex'' (1999)\n*''Rome: Power & Glory'' (1999)\n*''National Geographic: The Battle For Midway'' produced by [[Michael Rosenfeld]] (1999)\n*''[[In the Light of Reverence]]'' (2001)\n*''Color of War''\n*''[[Out of the Blue (2002 film)|Out of the Blue]]'' (2002)\n*''The Shapes of Life: Origins'' (2002)\n*''The Four Agreements: A Practical Guide to Personal Freedom'' by [[Don Miguel Ruiz]]\n*''The Fifth Agreement: A Practical Guide to Self-Mastery'' by [[Don Miguel Ruiz]]\n*''[[Oil on Ice]]'' (2004)\n*''The Voice of Knowledge : A Practical Guide to Inner Peace (Toltec Wisdom)'' by [[Don Miguel Ruiz]] (2004)\n*''Kursk: A Submarine In Troubled Waters'' by [[Jean-Michel Carr\u00e9]] (2004)\n*''National Geographic: Guns, Germs, and Steel'' (Jared Diamond, 2005)\n*''[[Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room]]'' (2005)\n*''Understanding: Extraterrestrials''\n*''[[The Tribe (2005 film)|The Tribe]]'' (2005)\n*''National Geographic Explorer \u2013 Journey to an Alien Moon'' produced by Mark Mannucci\n*''National Geographic: Lost Treasures of Afghanistan''  produced by [[James Barrat]] (2006)\n*''National Geographic: [[The Gospel of Judas]]''  produced by James Barrat (2006)\n*''[[The War Prayer]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Fog City Mavericks]]'' (2007)\n*''Hippies'' (2007)\n*''[[Stealing America: Vote by Vote (film)|Stealing America: Vote by Vote]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Torturing Democracy]]'' (2008)\n*''What If Cannabis Cured Cancer''\n*''Illicit: The Dark Trade'' (2008)\n*''National Geographic Explorer: Congo Bush Pilots'' producer/director/writer by Tony Gerber (2008)\n*''Wings of Thunder'' (2009)\n*''National Geographic Explorer: {{cite web |url=http://docuwiki.net/index.php?title=Easter_Island_Underworld |title= Easter Island Underworld}}'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petercoyote.com/documentaries.html|title=Documentaries|author=|date=|website=www.petercoyote.com|accessdate=April 30, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929052456/http://www.petercoyote.com/documentaries.html|archivedate=September 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*''National Geographic Explorer : The Virus Hunters'' (2009)\n*''National Geographic Explorer : Inside Guantanamo Bay'' (2009)\n*''[[The National Parks: America's Best Idea]]'' directed by [[Ken Burns]] (2009)\n*''[[Full Color Football: The History of the American Football League]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Reclaiming Their Voice: The Native American Vote in New Mexico & Beyond (film)|Reclaiming Their Voice: The Native American Vote in New Mexico & Beyond]]'' (2009)\n*''For the Rights of All: Ending Jim Crow in Alaska''\n*''The Top 100: NFL's Greatest Players'' (2010)\n*''[[Connected: An Autoblogography About Love, Death, & Technology]]'' (2011)\n*''I Am Fishead: Are Corporate Leaders Psychopaths?'' (2011)\n*''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]]'' by [[Ken Burns]] (2011)\n*''White Water, Black Gold'' (2011)\n*''NHL 36: Niklas Lidstrom'' (2012)\n*''NHL 36: Mike Richards'' (2012)\n*''NHL 36: James Neal'' (2012)\n*''[[The Dust Bowl (film)|The Dust Bowl]]'' (2012) Host and narrator of PBS miniseries directed by [[Ken Burns]]\n*''PBS: The Ghost Army'' (2013)\n*''Big Bend: Life on the Edge'' (2013)\n*''PBS: [[The Roosevelts (miniseries)|The Roosevelts: An Intimate History]]'' by Ken Burns (2014)\n*''Pretty Slick'' by James Fox (2014)\n*''Sands of War'' (2015)\n*''The Illusionists'' by Elena Rossini (2015)\n*''[[The Vietnam War (film)|The Vietnam War]]'' by Ken Burns and Lynn Novick (2017)\n*''Oregon Experience: Hanford'' Oregon Public Broadcasting (2013)\n*''PBS: Moscone: A Legacy of Change'' (2018)\n*\"\"The Etruscan Smile\" (2018)\n*''PBS: [[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]'' by Ken Burns (2019)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Peter Coyote (1998). ''Sleeping Where I Fall: A Chronicle''. {{ISBN|1-58243-011-X}}. Autobiography.\n* Michael Corrigan (2008). ''A Year and a Day: A Grief Journal''. Idaho State University. {{ISBN|9780937834763}}. Includes Peter Coyote's emails to Michael Corrigan after Corrigan lost his wife.\n* Peter Coyote (2015). ''The Rainman's Third Cure: An Irregular Education''. {{ISBN|1619024969}}. Memoir.\n\n===Illustrator===\n*[[Emmett Grogan]] (1990) ''Ringolevio: A Life Played for Keeps'', autobiography\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.petercoyote.com/ Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|1075|Peter Coyote}}\n* [http://www.diggers.org/ The Diggers Archives]\n* [http://www.diggers.org/freefall/freefall.html The Free-Fall Chronicles] excerpts from ''Sleeping Where I Fall''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071015123645/http://heyokamagazine.com/HEYOKA.9.PeterCoyote.htm Heyoka Magazine Interview with John LeKay]\n* [http://www.lib.ucdavis.edu/dept/specol/collections/manuscripts/index.php?collection=67 Peter Coyote Papers] at [http://www.lib.ucdavis.edu/dept/specol/ Special Collections Dept.], University Library, University of California, Davis\n* [http://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=3770 Peter Coyote] (Aveleyman)\n* [http://eurochannel.com/en/Interview-with-Peter-Coyote.html Interview with Peter Coyote] at [[Eurochannel]]\n* [https://omeka.binghamton.edu/omeka/items/show/841\u00a0Interview with Peter Coyote] by Stephen McKiernan,\u00a0Binghamton University Libraries Center for the Study of the 1960s, July 22, 2010\n\n{{EmmyAward Narrator}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coyote, Peter}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American pacifists]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American Sephardic Jews]]\n[[Category:American Zen Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n[[Category:Buddhist pacifists]]\n[[Category:Buddhists of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Diggers (theater)]]\n[[Category:Dwight Morrow High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grinnell College alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Narrator Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Englewood, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Theatre in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor, voice actor, and director}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Peter Coyote at Durell Vineyard, Sonoma, April 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 187px\n| caption = Coyote in 2019\n| birth_name=Robert Peter Cohon<ref name=gale>''Contemporary Authors Online'' (2002) Gale, Detroit</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1941|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Sebastopol, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = actor, author, director, screenwriter, narrator\n| years_active = 1967\u2013present\n| alma_mater = [[Grinnell College]], B.A. 1964<br>[[San Francisco State University]]\n| partner   = Eileen Ewing (1965-1972)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Marilyn McCann|1975|1998|reason=divorced}}<ref>\"Peter Coyote\", ''Contemporary Theatre, Film and Television'' Vol. 57 (2004)  Gale, Detroit</ref><br>{{marriage|Stefanie Pleet|1998|2015|reason=divorced}}\n| children= 2\n| website = [http://www.petercoyote.com Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Peter Coyote''' (born '''Robert Peter Cohon'''; October 10, 1941)<ref name=gale/><ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petercoyote.com/biography.html |title=Official Website, Biography |publisher=Petercoyote.com |date=1941-10-10 |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> is an American actor, author, director, screenwriter and narrator of films, theatre, television and [[audiobook]]s. He is known for his work in various films such as ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982), ''[[Cross Creek (film)|Cross Creek]]'' (1983), ''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]'' (1985), ''[[Patch Adams (film)|Patch Adams]]'' (1998), ''[[Erin Brockovich (film)|Erin Brockovich]]'' (2000), ''[[A Walk to Remember]]'' (2002), ''[[Hemingway & Gellhorn]]'' (2012) and ''[[Good Kill]]'' (2014). He was also known as the \"Voice of Oscar\" for the [[72nd Academy Awards]] ceremony, the first [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] announcer to be seen on-camera.<ref>{{cite web|title=72nd Academy Awards - March 26, 2000|url=http://www.petercoyote.com/oscars2000.html|website=PeterCoyote.com|accessdate=28 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611172747/http://www.petercoyote.com/oscars2000.html|archivedate=June 11, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCoyote's voice work includes his narration for the opening ceremony of the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iPad]] Retina Display campaign. He narrated the [[PBS]] series ''[[The Pacific Century]]'' (1992), winning an [[Emmy Award|Emmy]], and eight documentaries directed or produced by [[Ken Burns]]: ''[[The West (miniseries)|The West]]'' (1996), ''[[The National Parks: America's Best Idea]]'' (2009), ''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]]'' (2011), ''[[The Dust Bowl (miniseries)|The Dust Bowl]]'' (2012), ''[[The Roosevelts (miniseries)|The Roosevelts: An Intimate History]]'' (2014), ''[[The Vietnam War (TV series)|The Vietnam War]]'' (2017), ''The [[Mayo Clinic]]: Faith--Hope--Science'' (2018), and ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]] (2019). ''He won a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator]] in 2015 for his work on ''The Roosevelts''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/peter-coyote|title=Peter Coyote|website=Emmys.com|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref> His voice has often been said to resemble that of actor [[Henry Fonda]].''<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web |author=Tim.McLarty |url=http://www.ontrackblog.com/2011/06/creative-excellence-fridays-voice-of.html |title=Comment on Coyote's voice and 1992 Emmy |publisher=Ontrackblog.com |date=2011-06-17 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315041629/http://www.ontrackblog.com/2011/06/creative-excellence-fridays-voice-of.html |archivedate=March 15, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>''\n\nCoyote was one of the founders of the [[Diggers (theater)|Diggers]], an [[anarchism|anarchist]] [[Improvisational theatre|improv group]] active in [[Haight-Ashbury]] during the mid-1960s. Coyote was also an actor, writer and director with the [[San Francisco Mime Troupe]]; his prominence in the San Francisco [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] scene led to his being interviewed for the book ''Voices from the Love Generation''. He acted in and directed the first cross-country tour of ''The Minstrel Show'', and his play ''Olive Pits'', co-authored with Mime Troupe member [[Peter Berg (bioregionalist)|Peter Berg]], won the troupe an [[Obie Award]] from ''[[The Village Voice]]''. Coyote became a member, and later chairman, of the [[California Arts Council]] from 1975 to 1983. In the late 1970s, he shifted from acting on stage to acting in [[film]]s. In the 1990s and 2000s (decade), he acted in several television shows. He speaks fluent [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[French language|French]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://redroom.com/member/peter-coyote/bio |title=Peter Coyote's Biography |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |publisher=redroom |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220230433/http://redroom.com/member/peter-coyote/bio |archivedate=February 20, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/news0304.html |title=Spring 2004 Newsletter |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |publisher=petercoyote.com }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCoyote was born in [[New York City]], the son of Ruth (n\u00e9e Fidler) and Morris Cohon, an investment banker.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/23/Peter-Coyote.html |title=Peter Coyote profile at Film Reference.com |publisher=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307142509/http://www.filmreference.com/film/23/Peter-Coyote.html |archivedate=March 7, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> His father was of [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic Jewish]] descent and his mother came from a working-class [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi Jewish]] family. Her father, trained as a [[rabbi]] in Russia, escaped being drafted into the [[Imperial Russian Army]], and eventually ran a small candy store in [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"family\"/> Coyote \"was raised in a highly intellectual, cultural but unreligious family\",<ref name=\"family\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/7741/edition_id/147/format/html/displaystory.html |title=Peter Coyote: 'an outsider with a Jewish sense of humor' |publisher=Jewishsf.com |date=1998-01-09 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430064121/http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/7741/edition_id/147/format/html/displaystory.html |archivedate=April 30, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> involved in left-wing politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/32919/format/html/displaystory.html |title='&#39;Tie Dayenu'&#39; |publisher=Jewishsf.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410075408/http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/32919/format/html/displaystory.html |archivedate=April 10, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He grew up in [[Englewood, New Jersey]]<ref>[http://www.jackmagazine.com/issue4/petercoyotebio.html Peter Coyote biodata] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906111248/http://www.jackmagazine.com/issue4/petercoyotebio.html |date=September 6, 2008 }}, ''[[Jack Magazine]]''. Accessed November 25, 2007. \"At fourteen he was a campaign worker in the [[Adlai Stevenson II|Adlai Stevenson]] presidential campaign in his home town of Englewood New Jersey.\"</ref> and graduated from [[Dwight Morrow High School]] there in 1960. Coyote later said that he was \"half black and half white inside\" due to the strong influence of Susie Nelson, his family's [[African Americans|African-American]] housekeeper.<ref>[http://www.hendersondispatch.com/index.php?pSetup=hendersondailydispatch&curDate=20080429&pageToLoad=showFreeArticle.php&type=art&index=01 \"Susie Nelson's other son\" by Al Wheless, ''[[The Daily Dispatch]]'', [[Henderson, North Carolina]], April 29, 2008]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> Coyote is the maternal uncle of prominent librarian [[Jessamyn West (librarian)|Jessamyn West]].\n\nWhile a student at [[Grinnell College]] in 1961, Coyote was one of the organizers of a group of twelve students who traveled to Washington, D.C. during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] supporting President [[John F. Kennedy]]'s \"peace race\". Kennedy invited the group into the [[White House]], the first time protesters had ever been so recognized, and they met for several hours with [[McGeorge Bundy]]. The group received wide press coverage. They [[mimeograph]]ed the resulting headlines and sent them to every college in the United States.<ref name=\"bio\"/> He was also in a band called the Kittatinny Mountain Boys. Referenced in The Rainman's Third Cure by Peter Coyote.<ref name=\"Coyote2015\">{{cite book|author=Peter Coyote|title=The Rainman's Third Cure: An Irregular Education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ma32BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA108|date=1 April 2015|publisher=Catapult|isbn=978-1-61902-635-3|pages=108\u2013}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nOnce he graduated from Grinnell with a BA in English literature in 1964,<ref name=\"bio\"/> he moved to the [[West Coast of the United States|west coast]], despite having been accepted at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]],<ref name=\"bio\"/> and commenced working towards a master's degree in [[creative writing]] at [[San Francisco State University]].<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n===Name change===\nWhile still at Grinnell, Coyote ingested [[peyote]] and had a hallucination in which he saw his footprints as [[coyote]] paw-prints. A few years later, he came across ''Coyote's Journal'', a poetry magazine, and recognized its logo as the same paw-prints he had seen during his drug-induced experience. This caused him to change his name to Coyote, after meeting [[Rolling Thunder (person)|Rolling Thunder]] (John Pope), a self-styled [[Shamanism|shaman]], who believed the experience was spiritually significant.<ref>\"Krassner reviews 'Sleeping Where I Fall' by Peter Coyote\" (Sep/Oct 1999) ''[[Tikkun (magazine)|Tikkun]]'' Vol.14 No.5 pp. 71-74</ref>\n\n==Countercultural activities==\nAfter a short apprenticeship at the San Francisco [[Actor's Workshop]], he joined the [[San Francisco Mime Troupe]], a radical political street theater whose members were arrested for performing in parks without permits. Coyote acted, wrote scripts, and directed in the Mime Troupe. Coyote directed the first cross-country tour of ''The Minstrel Show, Civil Rights in a Cracker Barrel,''<ref name=\"bio\"/> a controversial play closed by authorities in several cities.<ref>\"Mime Troupe Gets Injunction, Acclaim\" (6 Feb 1968) ''Los Angeles Times''</ref>\n\nFrom 1967 to 1975, Coyote was a prominent member of the San Francisco Haight-Ashbury [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] community and a founding member, along with [[Emmett Grogan]], Peter Berg, Judy Goldhaft, Kent Minault, Nina Blasenheim, David Simpson, Jane Lapiner, and Billy Murcott, of the [[Diggers (theater)|Diggers]], an anarchist group known for operating anonymously and without money.<ref name=\"diggers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diggers.org/overview.htm |title=Overview: who were (are) the Diggers? |publisher=Diggers.org |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> They created provocative \"theater\" events designed to heighten awareness of problems associated with the notion of private property, consumerism, and identification with one's work. They fed nearly 600 people a day for \"free\", asking only that people pass through a six-foot by six-foot square known as The Free Frame of Reference. They ran a Free Store,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diggers.org/free_store.htm |title=Digger Virtual Free Store |publisher=Diggers.org |date=1967-10-14 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170248/http://www.diggers.org/free_store.htm |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"thesun\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issues/426/against_the_grain |title=Against The Grain: Peter Coyote On Buddhism, Capitalism, And The Enduring Legacy Of The Sixties |author=David Kupfer |journal=[[The Sun (magazine)|The Sun]] |issue=426 |accessdate=May 20, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419234605/http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issues/426/against_the_grain |archivedate=April 19, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> (where not only the goods, but the management roles were free), a Free Medical Clinic, and even a short-lived Free Bank.<ref name=\"diggers\"/> The Diggers evolved into a group known as the Free Family, which established chains of communes around the [[Pacific Northwest]] and [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]]. Coyote was the best known resident of the [[Black Bear Ranch]] commune in [[Siskiyou County, California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diggers.org/freefall/elsa.html |title=The Free-Fall Chronicles: Elsa's Story |publisher=Diggers.org |date=1996-06-08 |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303192835/http://www.diggers.org/freefall/elsa.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe was a friend of [[Rolling Thunder (person)|Rolling Thunder]], a purported Shoshone Medicine man. He has also been a friend of [[Leonard Peltier]], a Native American activist and member of the [[American Indian Movement]] (AIM) since the 1960s and, along with author [[Peter Mathiessen]], is one of Peltier's two non-native advisers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/chepesiuk1.html |title=Hollywood Radical |publisher=Peter Coyote |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172300/http://www.petercoyote.com/chepesiuk1.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOf this period of his life, Coyote wrote in ''Sleeping Where I Fall,'' <blockquote>The failure to curb personal indulgence was a major collective error. Our journeys down the path along with [[Paul Verlaine|Verlaine]] and [[Arthur Rimbaud|Rimbaud]], disordered our senses, senselessly wasted young lives, and often sabotaged what we labored so diligently to construct. ... It is the artist's responsibility to manifest sanity and health\u2014something we did not fully understand.<ref>Peter Coyote (1998) ''Sleeping Where I Fall: A Chronicle,'' Counterpoint Press, Berkeley, California {{ISBN|1-58243-011-X}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Discovering Zen==\nCoyote had first discovered [[Zen]] in his teens via the works of [[Jack Kerouac]], [[Gary Snyder]], and other [[Beat Generation|Beats]]. Coyote met Snyder with the Diggers and was impressed with Snyder's \"gravitas and elegance, his care and deliberation\".<ref name=\"thesun\"/><ref name=\"sweep\">{{cite interview |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/sweepingzen.html |title=Peter Hosho Jishi Coyote |interviewer=Sweeping Zen |date=June 16, 2008 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013171201/http://petercoyote.com/sweepingzen.html |archivedate=October 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1975, Coyote undertook meditation practice and eventually became a dedicated practitioner of American Zen Buddhism, moving into the [[San Francisco Zen Center]].<ref name=\"sweep\"/><ref name=\"zenbones\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petercoyote.com/zenflesh.html |title=Zen Flesh, Zen Bones |publisher=Petercoyote.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> He was later ordained a lay priest in the [[S\u014dt\u014d]] tradition and was ordained as a Zen Priest in 2015.<ref name=\"sweep\"/><ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Peter Coyote lay ordained in Mill Valley, CA | url=http://www.cuke.com/sangha_news/coyote%20ordain.html | work=Cuke Sangha News | date=April 22, 2007 | accessdate=June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Joyce Kleiner |title=Coyote reflects on wild dogs and the next 1,000 years |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/millvalley021512.html |work=The Mill Valley Herald |date=February 15, 2012 |accessdate=May 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nCoyote performed [[audiobook]] recordings of [[Shunryu Suzuki]]'s ''[[Zen Mind, Beginner's Mind]]'', [[Paul Reps]]'s ''[[Zen Flesh, Zen Bones]]'' as well as narrating the documentary ''Inquiry into the Great Matter: A History of Zen Buddhism''.<ref name=\"zenbones\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofzendvd.com |title=''Inquiry into the Great Matter: A History of Zen Buddhism'' |accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== San Francisco Arts Commission and the California Arts Council ==\nIn keeping with his dedication to community-based art, Peter Coyote was employed in the early 1970s by the [[San Francisco Arts Commission]] in the historical Neighborhood Arts Program (NAP), with funding from the [[Comprehensive Employment and Training Act]] (CETA, Pub.L. 93\u2013203), a United States federal law enacted by Congress, signed into law by President Richard Nixon in 1973, to train workers and provide them with jobs in the public service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/R?d095:FLD001:@4(Manpower+training+programs) |title=Manpower training programs, The Library of Congress |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14}}</ref> The San Francisco Arts Commission's Neighborhood Arts/CETA Program was the first in the country to use CETA funds to hire artists to work in service to a city.<ref>{{YouTube|O8awBsmvtnc}}</ref> From this position, Coyote was appointed by [[Jerry Brown|Governor Jerry Brown]] to be a member of the [[California Arts Council]], the state agency which determines art policy for the state. He served on the CAC from 1975 to 1983. After his first year, Coyote was elected chairman by his peers three years in a row. During his tenure as chairman, the Council's overhead expenses dropped from 50% to 15%, the lowest in the State, and the Arts Council budget rose from $1 million to $16 million. His council introduced the idea of artists as \"creative problem solvers.\" By paying artists to \"solve problems for the state\" rather than to make art, they bypassed the objections of many conservative lawmakers. Coyote engineered relationships with 14 departments of the State of California, which began to use artists in a variety of capacities, paying 50 cents on the dollar for it. The policy and the council were an immense success, giving Coyote the confidence (after 12 years in the counterculture) to try his hand at mainstream film-acting.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\n==Film and television acting==\nIn 1978, Coyote began acting again (\"to shake the rust out\") appearing in plays at San Francisco's award-winning [[Magic Theatre]]. While playing the lead in the world premiere of [[Sam Shepard]]'s ''[[True West (play)|True West]]'', a Hollywood agent approached him, and his film career began with ''[[Die Laughing (film)|Die Laughing]]'' (1980). He gave supporting performances in ''[[Tell Me a Riddle (film)|Tell Me a Riddle]]'' (1980), ''[[Southern Comfort (1981 film)|Southern Comfort]]'' (1981) and as the mysterious scientist \"Keys\" in ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982). He was seriously considered for the role of [[Indiana Jones]] in ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981), and auditioned for the part. Coyote's first starring role was in the science fiction adventure ''[[Timerider: The Adventure of Lyle Swann]]'' (1982). He also starred in ''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]'' (1985) and ''[[Outrageous Fortune (film)|Outrageous Fortune]]'' (1987). Since then, he has made more than 120 films for theaters and television and has played starring roles for many directors, including [[Roman Polanski]] (''[[Bitter Moon]]''), [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]] (''[[Kika (1993 film)|Kika]]''), [[Martin Ritt]] (''[[Cross Creek (film)|Cross Creek]]''), [[Jean-Paul Rappeneau]] (''[[Bon Voyage (2003 film)|Bon Voyage]]''), [[Diane Kurys]] (''[[A Man in Love (1987 film)|A Man in Love]]'') and [[Walter Salles]] (''[[A Grande Arte|Exposure]]''). For his 1990 guest appearance on the television series ''[[Road to Avonlea]]'', he received his first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination.\n\n[[Leonard Maltin]] once wrote, \"Coyote's no rubber-stamp leading man\", but he seems comfortable with that. \"I'm a [[Zen]] Buddhist student first, actor second\", Coyote has said. \"If I can't reconcile the two lives, I'll stop acting. I spend more time off-screen than on.\" In addition to his movie work in more recent films such as ''[[Sphere (1998 film)|Sphere]]'', ''[[A Walk to Remember]]'', and ''[[Erin Brockovich (film)|Erin Brockovich]]'', Coyote has also appeared in many made-for-TV movies and miniseries, and he does commercial voice-overs. Coyote was cast in lead roles on several television series: ''[[The 4400]]'' in 2004 and ''[[The Inside (TV series)|The Inside]]'' in 2005. After ''The Inside'' was canceled, Coyote returned to ''The 4400'' as a special guest star for their two-part season finale, then joined the cast of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s series ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'' as the [[Vice President of the United States]], and the next year did a four episode turn as [[Sally Field]]'s disreputable boyfriend in ''[[Brothers & Sisters (2006 TV series)|Brothers & Sisters]]''.\n\n==Narration==\nIn 2005, Coyote served as the narrator for several prominent projects including the documentary film ''[[Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room]]'' and the ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]''-produced [[PBS]] documentary based on [[Jared Diamond]]'s ''[[Guns, Germs, and Steel]]''. He also narrated an episode of the series ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' in April 2006. In 2008, he narrated ''[[Torturing Democracy]]'', a documentary produced by [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] which details the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush administration]]'s use of \"[[enhanced interrogation techniques]]\" in the [[War on Terror]]. He also narrated the 12-hour [[Ken Burns]] series on the [[The National Parks: America's Best Idea|National Parks]], and 15 episodes for the ''[[National Geographic Explorer]]'' series. In 2010 he narrated the documentary ''Solitary Confinement'' on the effect of long-term isolation, with footage taken from [[Colorado State Penitentiary]] where all prisoners are held this way. In 2014, he appeared in the [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] television series ''[[Perception (American TV series)|Perception]]'', as the father of the main character, Dr. Daniel Pierce, and narrated Burns' [[The Roosevelts (miniseries)|''The Roosevelts: An Intimate History'']]; the latter saw him win his first [[Primetime Emmy Award]]. In 2019, he narrated Burns' PBS documentary ''[[Country Music (miniseries)]]''.<ref>https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nCoyote's [[left-wing politics]] are evident in his articles for ''[[Mother Jones magazine|Mother Jones]]'' magazine, some of which he wrote as a delegate to the [[1996 Democratic National Convention]]; in his disagreements with [[David Horowitz (conservative writer)|David Horowitz]]; and in his autobiography ''Sleeping Where I Fall''. In 2006, he developed a political television show for [[Link TV]] called \"The Active Opposition\" and in 2007 created ''Outside the Box with Peter Coyote'' starting on Link TV's special, Special: ''The End of Oil \u2013 Part 2''.\n\nMany of Coyote's stories from the 1967 to 1975 [[counter-culture]] period are included in his memoir, ''Sleeping Where I Fall,'' published by [[Counterpoint Press]] in April 1998. One of the stories incorporated into his book is \"Carla's Story,\" about a 16-year-old mother who lived communally with Coyote, and who, after learning of her husband's murder, became a drug addict, then a prostitute, had her children stolen, and continued to spiral downhill until she turned her life around. This story was published in ''[[Zyzzyva (magazine)|Zyzzyva]]'', and awarded the 1993\u20131994 [[Pushcart Prize]]. He also states he was a close friend of singer [[Janis Joplin]]. Coyote has a website,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petercoyote.com/ |title=Peter Coyote's website |publisher=Petercoyote.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015012/http://www.petercoyote.com/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> which features the titles of all his movies and extended samples of much of his writing. He is a member at RedRoom.com, a website for authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redroom.com/member/peter-coyote|title=Redroom.com - Earn Money - Save Money - Multiply Money|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302034224/http://redroom.com/member/peter-coyote|archivedate=March 2, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, his memoir ''The Rainman's Third Cure: An Irregular Education'' was released, where he \"provides portraits of mentors that shaped him\u2014including his violent, intimidating father, a bass player, a Mafia Consiglieri, and beat poet Gary Snyder, who introduced him to the practice of Zen.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Coyote's Path From Street Theater To the Big Screen to Zen|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/peter-coyotes-path-street-theater-big-screen-zen/|publisher=[[WNYC]]|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426025851/http://www.wnyc.org/story/peter-coyotes-path-street-theater-big-screen-zen/|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Actor===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n*''[[Alcatraz: The Whole Shocking Story]]'' (1980) as Lt. Micklin \n*''[[Die Laughing (film)|Die Laughing]]'' (1980) as Davis\n*''[[Southern Comfort (1981 film)|Southern Comfort]]'' (1981) as Sergeant Poole\n*''[[Isabel's Choice]]'' (1981 TV film) as Wynn Thomas\n*''[[Timerider: The Adventure of Lyle Swann]]'' (1982) as Porter Reese\n*''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982) as Keys\n*''[[Endangered Species (1982 film)|Endangered Species]]'' (1982) as Steele\n*''[[Strangers Kiss|Strangers' Kiss]]'' (1983) Stanley, the Director\n*''[[Cross Creek (film)|Cross Creek]]'' (1983) as Norton Baskin\n*''[[Slayground]]'' (1983) as Stone \n*''[[Heartbreakers (1984 film)|Heartbreakers]]'' (1984) as Arthur Blue\n*''[[The Legend of Billie Jean]]'' (1985) as Det. Larry Ringwald\n*''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]'' (1985) as Thomas Krasny\n*''[[The Blue Yonder]]'' (1985) as Max Knickerbocker\n*''[[Outrageous Fortune (film)|Outrageous Fortune]]'' (1987) as Michael Sanders\n*''[[A Man in Love (1987 film)|Un homme amoureux]]'' (1987) as Steve Elliott\n*''[[Echoes in the Darkness]]'' (1987 TV mini-series) as William Bradfield Jr.\n*''[[Heart of Midnight (film)|Heart of Midnight]]'' (1988) as Sharpe/Larry\n*'